DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T081000Z
DTEND:20260323T082000Z
SUMMARY:CNCF Platform Engineering Technical Community Group Update - Katie Greenley\, Chris Plank\, Colin Griffin & Atulpriya Sharma\, CNCF Platform Engineering Technical Community Group
DESCRIPTION:Come along and listen to the leaders of the CNCF's Platform Engineering Technical Community Group give a quick update on what the community has been up to since KubeCon Atlanta\, the initiatives underway and planned as well as what events they are running at KubeCon Amsterdam.\n\n\n
CATEGORIES:PLATFORM ENGINEERING DAY
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room F\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:cfff70ed08086264eb860c42fada9b22
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/cfff70ed08086264eb860c42fada9b22
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T081000Z
DTEND:20260323T083500Z
SUMMARY:OTel Me About It: Latest Updates in WASI OTel - Caleb Schoepp\, Fermyon & Andrew Steurer\, Independent
DESCRIPTION:With WebAssembly firmly in production\, it is more important than ever to have observable Wasm workloads. OpenTelemetry is the gold standard for modern observability and now it’s coming to WebAssembly. This talk presents the WASI OTel proposal\, a new WASI interface that enables using OpenTelemetry SDKs from within your Wasm components. You’ll see how traces\, metrics\, and logs can be emitted seamlessly from Wasm applications\, with a live demo using Spin\, the leading framework for building and running serverless Wasm workloads. We’ll unpack the key design choices behind WASI OTel and show how the WebAssembly component model unlocks powerful new capabilities\, such as automatically enriching traces with information from the component graph. We’ll close with an update on the proposal’s progress within both the WebAssembly and OpenTelemetry communities\, and how this work is shaping the future of observability for Wasm in production.
CATEGORIES:WASMCON
LOCATION:E106-108\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:5fd1d5acbe8ab9d6686be9e2ee60adce
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/5fd1d5acbe8ab9d6686be9e2ee60adce
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T081500Z
DTEND:20260323T084000Z
SUMMARY:Our Journey To a Unified Developer Experience With Backstage - Symbat Nurbay & Xicu Piñera\, Booking.com
DESCRIPTION:Over the past 3 years\, our organization has used Backstage as a central portal where 1.5k employees access 45 custom tools and 400K software assets. But to most people\, it felt like many separate tools living side-by-side—helpful but not unified—and we realized we weren’t using Backstage's full potential. Last year\, we rethought our approach. Instead of treating the portal as a container for tools\, we aimed to create a unified experience that helps people work across them. The idea came from our weekly meetings\, where we constantly switched between tools to check health\, metrics\, and alerts for our team's services. That workflow was slow and fragmented. To fix it\, we built a centralized place that connects key signals from those tools in one view. This has changed how we run weekly reviews and how we use the portal daily. This talk shares our path from “a collection of tools” to a unified experience—how we redesigned it\, the technical and organizational challenges\, and what we learned.
CATEGORIES:BACKSTAGECON
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room E\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:50e4efde431832f47aa917e047051c87
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/50e4efde431832f47aa917e047051c87
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T081500Z
DTEND:20260323T084000Z
SUMMARY:Advancing Machine to Machine Workflows with the SPIFFE Identity Provider - Andrew Block\, Red Hat & Maia Iyer\, IBM Research
DESCRIPTION:Most Keycloak users start by configuring realms\, clients\, and roles by hand—but that doesn’t scale. As organizations adopt multi-tenant and cloud-native applications\, manual configuration becomes a bottleneck and a source of security drift. \n \nThis session shows an approach for making Keycloak configuration declarative and repeatable. We’ll explore how to represent Keycloak realms and clients as code\, how to bootstrap client credentials automatically\, and how to connect Keycloak with trusted workload identities using SPIFFE/SPIRE so you'll never worry about copying a client secret ever again. \n \nYou’ll see real-world patterns for automating Keycloak setup across environments\, including how to reconcile configuration drift\, enforce consistent RBAC policies\, and safely manage client registration at scale. By the end\, you’ll know how to make Keycloak management as easy—and as reliable—as any modern DevOps workflow.
CATEGORIES:KEYCLOAKCON
LOCATION:Hall 7 | Room A\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:049cabe2f38214522328fdf1070b6a7d
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/049cabe2f38214522328fdf1070b6a7d
END:VEVENT
