BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T084000Z
DTEND:20260323T090500Z
SUMMARY:Air France–KLM’s GitOps Takeoff: Real Stories From the Flight Deck - Alaoui Echerif Amine & Ravi Ramrattan\, Air France KLM
DESCRIPTION:When Air France–KLM started its GitOps journey\, the biggest challenge wasn’t the tool\, it was THE TRUST. The Teams were used to centralized operations\, manual gates\, and direct control over production systems. Moving to GitOps meant automation\, transparency\, and letting Git drive the change process. That shift raised questions: Would we lose control? Could teams make safe changes on their own without platform owner?\nThis talk shares how we navigated those fears and turned them into a model for shared ownership. Using Flux and CI/CD\, we built a GitOps foundation that gives CyberSecurity\, Observability\, and Network Engineering teams full autonomy to manage their tools\, all within a secure and auditable framework.\nWhy attend this talk?\nBecause it shows how a small idea from a small internal team around open source tooling can actually shift the direction of a large organization. It’s about starting small\, proving value fast\, and turning that into real cultural and technical change.
CATEGORIES:FLUXCON
LOCATION:Elicium 1\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:78cb0e33b3cb67dc6c6875205d5ca5aa
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/78cb0e33b3cb67dc6c6875205d5ca5aa
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T084000Z
DTEND:20260323T085000Z
SUMMARY:⚡Lightning Talk: A Case Study in Cross-Ecosystem Security Response - Lori Lorusso\, Rust Foundation
DESCRIPTION:Companies use multiple open source projects and programming languages in their product stack creating a potential ‘wheel of misfortune’ when thinking about the rise in software supply chain attacks. Taking it one step further malicious actors are targeting programming languages to get to the core of how products are built. The rise in attacks at the programming language level seen as recently as September 2025 has amplified the need for cross communication between language ecosystems. Using the phishing attacks on Rust and Python as a case study we will show how Alpha-Omega facilitated stronger links between ecosystems\, specifically the Rust Foundation and Python Software Foundation (grantees of Alpha-Omega) and how this helped improve security response times and outcomes when the phishing attacks were launched.
CATEGORIES:OPEN SOURCE SECURITYCON
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room D\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:409b0248fd48de8494d7b5968a3d75c1
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/409b0248fd48de8494d7b5968a3d75c1
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T084500Z
DTEND:20260323T085500Z
SUMMARY:⚡Lightning Talk: Philosophy Meets Backstage: An Unlikely Path To a Plugin - Mathilde Ançay\, HEIG-VD
DESCRIPTION:How long does it take to go from zero Backstage knowledge to shipping a plugin? This talk shares my experience building a “team mood” plugin during a six-week internship\, with no prior TypeScript\, React\, or Backstage experience.\n\nMy background in the arts and humanities\, and now in media engineering\, shaped how I approached this challenge\, focusing on human experience rather than infrastructure. The plugin was completed\, deployed\, and used internally. I’ll show how I learned the stack fundamentals\, explored Backstage’s architecture\, and set up a working build and deployment pipeline within that timeframe. I’ll walk through concrete timelines: which concepts took days versus hours\, the resources that accelerated progress\, and the roadblocks that slowed me down.\n\nFor teams evaluating Backstage adoption or planning developer onboarding\, this journey offers a practical reference point with real data\, key learnings\, and a reminder that creativity and empathy are just as valuable as code.
CATEGORIES:BACKSTAGECON
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room E\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:f5f562c81ef8593dfd602ee854cb3d17
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/f5f562c81ef8593dfd602ee854cb3d17
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T084500Z
DTEND:20260323T091000Z
SUMMARY:Are We Stuck With Helm Forever? A Landscape of Cloud Native CNF Management Options - Istvan Kispal\, Nokia Bell Labs & Liam Fallon\, Ericsson Software Technology
DESCRIPTION:Helm was the de facto tool to manage the lifecycle of LCMs for a very long time. It was the first tool to manage the LCM of complex workloads and provided a way to standardize on the management of CNF. But Helm has its limitations and the tool landscape evolved and diversified. There are tools focusing on platform customisation\, configuration management or GitOps. Each of them has different benefits and drawbacks. In this talk Liam and Istvan collects the most prominent options for CNF management\, explain the difference between them and compare benefits and drawbacks.
CATEGORIES:CLOUD NATIVE TELCO DAY
LOCATION:G104-105\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:debf419f82b558030edcb4ebf1b226a5
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/debf419f82b558030edcb4ebf1b226a5
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T084500Z
DTEND:20260323T091000Z
SUMMARY:The Keycloak-Token-Configuration Mistake\, 90% of All Developers Do (and How To Avoid It) - Niko Köbler IT-Beratung
DESCRIPTION:You deploy Keycloak\, everything works—or so you think. But there's a problem that almost everyone misses: Keycloak makes it deliberately easy for developers. By default\, it puts a lot of information into your tokens: roles\, claims\, metadata. At first\, this feels good because everything "just works."\n\nBut this comes with a price:\n🚨 Your tokens contain more data than necessary\n🚨 Recipients receive information they don't need or shouldn't know\n🚨 Data protection principles are not optimally implemented\n🚨 HTTP requests can fail due to tokens that are too large\n\nIn this talk\, you will learn:\n✅ Why Keycloak reveals “too much of a good thing” by default\n✅ Which token contents are really necessary (and which are not)\n✅ How to implement data minimization through targeted configuration\n✅ Practical settings and strategies for lean and secure tokens\n\nThe result:\nPrivacy-compliant tokens that contain only what the recipient needs—no more\, no less. Security by design instead of by chance.
CATEGORIES:KEYCLOAKCON
LOCATION:Hall 7 | Room A\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:2f5de6a93e3a57f64424e62aa42dfd98
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/2f5de6a93e3a57f64424e62aa42dfd98
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T084500Z
DTEND:20260323T091000Z
SUMMARY:Making Observability Work at the Edge - Julia Furst Morgado\, Dash0 & Graziano Casto\, Akamas
DESCRIPTION:Observability gets tricky when you take Kubernetes to the Edge. Sending full traces and metrics upstream doesn’t scale when every byte and millisecond count.\nThis talk introduces an ultra-optimized OpenTelemetry Micro-Collector strategy built for Edge environments. It demonstrates how to minimize overhead without losing visibility by applying smart data reduction techniques like Tail-Based Sampling and Lossless Batching directly on the device\, ensuring that only high-value telemetry such as errors and slow requests leave the Edge.\nThe session covers how to deploy a lightweight DaemonSet tuned for K3s or MicroK8s using the OpenTelemetry Collector Contrib\, integrate Fluent Bit for unified log ingestion\, and maintain data integrity during disconnections. It shows what it takes to make observability truly sustainable in constrained Edge environments.
CATEGORIES:KUBERNETES ON EDGE DAY
LOCATION:Emerald Room\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:37477add416dff8857ec5b668a011db6
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/37477add416dff8857ec5b668a011db6
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T084500Z
DTEND:20260323T085500Z
SUMMARY:⚡Lightning Talk: The < Meta /> Trick: Connecting Page Load To Backend Traces - Wolfgang Therrien\, Honeycomb
DESCRIPTION:You instrument your backend services with distributed tracing. You add OpenTelemetry to your browser application. But there's a gap\, your traces start when JavaScript loads\, missing everything that happened before: the server-side processing and the initial HTML delivery.\n\nWolfgang shares a useful pattern for embedding the OpenTelemetry trace-parent in a meta tag during HTML generation\, then reading it client-side to correlate document load\, Core Web Vitals\, and errors in a single distributed trace enabling you to query a single complete end-to-end trace for document load.\n\nWe’ll examine a common debugging scenario where the user reports "The product page feels slow."\n\nWithout this pattern\, you'd see disconnected signals rather than an explicit parent-child relationship. You'd likely waste time trying to correlate those signals or optimizing frontend code when the real fix is on the backend.
CATEGORIES:OBSERVABILITY DAY
LOCATION:Forum (Ground Floor)\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:606dc96841f88850dc9f63fa7160722f
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/606dc96841f88850dc9f63fa7160722f
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T084500Z
DTEND:20260323T091000Z
SUMMARY:Streamlining WebAssembly Builds with Bunny - Charalampos Mainas & Anastassios Nanos\, Nubis PC
DESCRIPTION:Building WebAssembly (Wasm) is challengingdue to fragmented ad-hoc scripts and custom toolchains that vary across languages\, runtimes\, and projects. This lack of cohesion increases maintenance overhead and makesreproducible builds difficult. Unlike container-based workflows\, current Wasm build processes are inconsistent and manual\, slowing adoption and complicating deployment across environments.Bunny is an open-source project that unifies how applications build against various frameworks and platforms\, including Wasm.Using a simple declarative configuration\, Bunny compiles source code to Wasm/WASI\, creates components\, and produces OCI-compatible artifacts ready for deployment on any runtime or orchestration platform.This session presents Bunny’s design and workflow\, showing how a consistent build interface simplifies Wasm development across environments. A live demo will illustrate how source code becomes a ready-to-run Wasm module using a simple declarative build process.
CATEGORIES:WASMCON
LOCATION:E106-108\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:01eb50abe05ca442d4e4ee3286931449
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/01eb50abe05ca442d4e4ee3286931449
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T085000Z
DTEND:20260323T085500Z
SUMMARY:ArgoCon l Sponsored Keynote: From Kubernetes to Anything: The Evolution of Promotion with Kargo - Jesse Suen\, Akuity
DESCRIPTION:Kargo began as a Kubernetes-native promotion tool\, designed to safely and continuously move container images and manifests through environments using GitOps principles. As delivery pipelines evolved\, so did Kargo\, expanding beyond clusters to coordinate the promotion of Terraform plans\, cloud infrastructure\, and other non-Kubernetes changes alongside application workloads.\n\nToday\, Kargo is taking the next step. With user-defined container steps\, promotion workflows are no longer limited to predefined integrations. Teams can now run arbitrary\, versioned logic as part of a promotion\, whether that’s executing custom validations\, invoking external APIs\, mutating infrastructure\, running tests\, or integrating with systems that don’t yet have first-class support.\n\nIn this talk\, we’ll show how Kargo has evolved from a Kubernetes-focused tool into a universal promotion layer. By combining GitOps\, policy-driven workflows\, and user-defined containers\, Kargo enables safe\, auditable promotion across Kubernetes\, Terraform\, and virtually any system your delivery pipeline depends on\, all within a single declarative workflow.
CATEGORIES:ARGOCON
LOCATION:Auditorium\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:c52be7afed815a203da6f38b1709173c
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/c52be7afed815a203da6f38b1709173c
