SUMMARY:Cloud Native AI + Kubeflow Day | Sponsored Keynote: Production AI Runs on Open Source Abstract - Gleb Evstropov\, Nebius
DESCRIPTION:Behind today’s large-scale AI systems is a layered open-source ecosystem. Kubernetes provides the foundation\, Slurm powers high-performance batch scheduling\, Ray enables distributed compute\, and frameworks like PyTorch and DeepSpeed drive model training. At Nebius\, we build our AI platform directly on top of these technologies — integrating cloud-native orchestration with HPC scheduling to support large-scale training and inference workloads. We’ve also contributed back to the ecosystem by open-sourcing Soperator\, a project that bridges Slurm and Kubernetes to combine topology-aware scheduling with cloud-native elasticity and automation.\n\nIn this short talk\, we’ll walk through how these open-source components fit together in real production environments and why building on open foundations enables better scalability\, portability\, and operational transparency for teams running AI at scale.
CATEGORIES:CLOUD NATIVE AI + KUBEFLOW DAY
LOCATION:Hall 7 | Room B\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:e1109736142a2dc762c67f87818ec133
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/e1109736142a2dc762c67f87818ec133
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T090000Z
DTEND:20260323T090500Z
SUMMARY:Observability Day | Sponsored Keynote: Beyond Observability: Intelligent Progressive Delivery with Feature Control - Sean O'Dell\, Dynatrace
DESCRIPTION:Observability has traditionally helped teams understand what happened after software was released. But as software delivery accelerates driven by cloud-native architectures\, AI-assisted development\, and continuous deployment\; insight alone is no longer sufficient. The next evolution is beyond observability: closing the loop between insight and action so teams can actively guide software behavior in production\, not just observe it.\n\nIn this talk\, we explore how modern platforms are evolving from passive observability toward intelligent software resilience by combining deep runtime context with progressive delivery controls. Over the past several years\, the industry has moved steadily “shift-left” and “shift-right\,” bringing debugging\, performance analysis\, security\, and compliance closer to both development and production. The result is richer context across the software lifecycle\, but also greater responsibility on teams to act quickly and safely when change introduces risk ￼ ￼.\n\nProgressive delivery is the missing link. Feature flags and experimentation allow teams to decouple deployment from release\, exposing new functionality gradually and selectively. When combined with observability\, features become first-class runtime entities—automatically correlated with performance\, reliability\, security signals\, and business outcomes. Instead of asking “what changed?” after an incident\, teams can see which feature\, for whom\, and with what impact in real time.\n\nThis talk introduces the concept of Intelligent Feature Delivery: progressive rollouts governed continuously by runtime telemetry and AI-driven guardrails. Rather than relying on static rules or manual approvals\, the system evaluates live behavior against baselines and objectives. If anomalies appear\, rollouts can pause\, adjust\, or roll back instantly—without redeployment. This creates a closed-loop control system where insight directly drives action\, reducing blast radius while increasing delivery velocity ￼.\n\nIn five minutes\, attendees will learn:\n • Why traditional observability is necessary but insufficient for high-velocity software delivery\n • How progressive delivery shifts risk management from deployment time to runtime\n • What it means to treat “the feature” as a unifying concept across engineering\, operations\, and business\n • How AI-powered guardrails enable safer experimentation\, faster recovery\, and clearer business attribution\n\nBeyond observability lies a future where platforms don’t just explain system\, they actively help operate them. Intelligent progressive delivery is a foundational step toward that future.
CATEGORIES:OBSERVABILITY DAY
LOCATION:Forum (Ground Floor)\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:62ec3bf23a5eff3bfc8aa8576b51aeb9
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/62ec3bf23a5eff3bfc8aa8576b51aeb9
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T090300Z
DTEND:20260323T090800Z
SUMMARY:Platform Engineering Day | Sponsored Keynote: Bridging the Local Kubernetes Gap for AI Developers - Saiyam Pathak\, vCluster
DESCRIPTION:Everyone is building platforms. Increasingly\, AI platforms with GPU scheduling\, multi-tenancy\, inference autoscaling.\nBut the developer experience starts long before production. It starts locally — testing models\, iterating on configs getting things working on a cluster for the first time.\n\nToday\, there's a gap between that local experience and what actually runs in production. Local clusters are great for getting started\, but when you need GPU access\, environment sharing\, or anything that resembles your real platform\, you're on your own. Developers end up jumping straight to cloud environments\, losing the fast feedback loop.\n\nIn this keynote\, I'll talk about closing that gap with vind (vCluster in Docker)\, &nbsp\;local Kubernetes that goes further. attach real GPU nodes over VPN\, pause and resume clusters\, share environments with your team. I'll show what makes it different from existing local cluster tools and how it gives AI developers the fast feedback loop they've been missing.
CATEGORIES:PLATFORM ENGINEERING DAY
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room F\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
