SUMMARY:Divide & Collaborate: Creating Scalable and Healthy Backstage Based Applications in a Big Organisation - Krzysztof Janota & Dusan Askovic\, ING Bank N.V.
DESCRIPTION:Backstage is a tool with a lot of potential and almost limitless possibilities. It works great when you are starting from scratch\, without any legacy\, or in smaller sized organisations. Building innovative new features with just a few people is easy. But how do you scale that approach? How do you make innovation is community driven? How do you make sure Backstage is still doing what you envisioned without polluting it with unwanted features? How do you make sure you’re not cutting down innovations?\n\nLarge scale enterprises often find themselves with dozens of developers with great ideas but no way of contributing to the success that Backstage can bring to their organisation.\n\nThis talk will describe tried and tested best practices and how we approach Backstage development as community in ING on a global scale.
CATEGORIES:BACKSTAGECON
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room E\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:436bc1b8505788d61441a8be1cae040a
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/436bc1b8505788d61441a8be1cae040a
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T094000Z
DTEND:20260323T100500Z
SUMMARY:Ethical Bias - Robert Glenn\, Glennium\, LLC & Diana Zhawn\, Kopacetic\, Inc.
DESCRIPTION:In this talk\, we explore how to design ethical\, behavior-aware AI agents that balance personalization with privacy and human autonomy. Drawing on both established engineering practices and emerging ethical frameworks\, we examine how ethical constraints can serve as drivers of better system design\, rather than limitations on innovation.We discuss how to build agents that learn from individual behavior while actively promoting accountability\, collaboration\, and well-being\, without crossing into exploitation\, surveillance\, or intrusion. Central to this approach is an understanding that AI systems are not just computational tools\, but participants in human communication.
CATEGORIES:CLOUD NATIVE AI + KUBEFLOW DAY
LOCATION:Hall 7 | Room C\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:73fe64e3cd795c25bb91a62d511b7eec
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/73fe64e3cd795c25bb91a62d511b7eec
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T094000Z
DTEND:20260323T100500Z
SUMMARY:The Sanity Check: Observability for AI Data Pipelines - David Aronchick\, Expanso
DESCRIPTION:Your AI just confidently gave a completely wrong answer. Why? Was it a bad model? Or was it poisoned by garbage data ingested three weeks ago from a rogue Salesforce update? You have no idea\, because your AI data pipeline is a complete black box.\n\nThis is a talk about lighting up that black box. We (from the teams that built Kubernetes and scaled Kinesis) will show you how to apply the hard-won SRE principles from hyper-scale data systems to your AI infrastructure. This isn't about model monitoring\; it's about data pipeline observability. We'll show you the architecture and tools required to trace a single bad prediction all the way back to the specific source data that caused it.\n\nYou'll leave knowing how to monitor for data freshness\, track lineage from source to token\, and alert on data drift before it silently corrupts your entire system.
CATEGORIES:CLOUD NATIVE AI + KUBEFLOW DAY
LOCATION:Hall 7 | Room B\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:aab564986088a26c582b7408ce94aefc
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/aab564986088a26c582b7408ce94aefc
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T094000Z
DTEND:20260323T100500Z
SUMMARY:The Autonomous Telco: AI Agents as First-Class Citizens in Cloud-Native Infrastructure- Samy Nitsche & Dorian Lenzner - Deutsche Telekom
DESCRIPTION:Network troubleshooting in cloud-native telco environments requires expert knowledge of complex protocols (NGAP\, PFCP\, GTP) and hours of manual analysis. This talk introduces KubeTrace\, a distributed packet capture system for Kubernetes that integrates AI agents into the observability stack via the Model Context Protocol (MCP). \n \nWe'll demonstrate how KubeTrace enables continuous packet capture with AI-friendly interfaces. You'll see AI agents diagnosing 5G core issues—from UE registration failures to inter-NF communication problems—by autonomously correlating packets across multiple interfaces and nodes in seconds. \n \nThe second half explores AI disruption in telco DevOps: automated security testing\, CI/CD pipelines where AI generates test cases from production traffic\, self-healing systems and continuous compliance auditing. \n \nLearn from real-world Deutsche Telekom experience building AI-first observability and witness how network engineers become orchestrators of AI operations.
CATEGORIES:CLOUD NATIVE TELCO DAY
LOCATION:G104-105\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:ae26e3e3dea81b5c5c5f6cea484e06cf
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/ae26e3e3dea81b5c5c5f6cea484e06cf
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T094000Z
DTEND:20260323T100500Z
SUMMARY:Model Context Protocol(MCP) Authorization for Enterprise Use Case With Keycloak - Yutaka Obuchi\, Hitachi\, Ltd.
DESCRIPTION:In the MCP community\, Enterprise-Managed Authorization for MCP is proposed as Specification Enhancement Proposal #646(SEP-646\, https://github.com/modelcontextprotocol/modelcontextprotocol/pull/646)\, which was proposed by one of Auth 2.1 spec authors and has just been merged as MCP Authorization Extensions on Oct 31st.\n\nThis proposal is intended to provide a solution for the authorization problem of MCP in enterprise use case and make\nMCP authorization enterprise-ready from both ux and security perspective.\n\nThe target problem is that users need to manually log in and consent to grant an Al agent access to each external resources one by one and it is hard to visualize those access enough for enterprise security.\nIt will be getting bigger with future explosion of Al agents.\n\nThe session will cover the following:\n- ﻿﻿the target problem and the solution of SEP-646\n- ﻿﻿Keycloak’s implementation for RFC7523\, which is prerequisite spec for SEP-646\n- implementation of SEP-646 using Keycloak
CATEGORIES:KEYCLOAKCON
LOCATION:Hall 7 | Room A\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:c7c842401b2e7c637b2f0aa9d488fa6a
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/c7c842401b2e7c637b2f0aa9d488fa6a
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T094000Z
DTEND:20260323T100500Z
SUMMARY:IoT Compute Unleashed: Transparent Offload From ESP32 To Edge Clusters - Anastassios Nanos & Charalampos Mainas\, Nubis PC
DESCRIPTION:How can a ESP32 microcontroller leverage Kubernetes for compute acceleration? This talk showcases how a tiny microcontroller can run inference on a full YOLOv11 model in less than 200ms! We leverage vAccel\, an open abstraction layer that allows IoT devices like the ESP32 to transparently offload ML inference and signal-processing tasks to nearby edge or cloud nodes. Through a lightweight agent and a unified API\, vAccel bridges heterogeneous devices\, enabling seamless offload without modifying application logic. The session demonstrates a real deployment where an ESP32 delegates inference to a GPU-backed Kubernetes node\, reducing latency and power consumption while preserving Kubernetes-native control and observability. Attendees will see how open acceleration can unify the Cloud–Edge–IoT stack through standard interfaces and reusable runtimes.
CATEGORIES:KUBERNETES ON EDGE DAY
LOCATION:Emerald Room\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:f3d5fff93d476f34308df1d36725b1ee
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/f3d5fff93d476f34308df1d36725b1ee
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T094000Z
DTEND:20260323T100500Z
SUMMARY:A Practical Blueprint for Evolving Observability Schemas - Benedikt Bongartz\, Red Hat & Sebastian Rabenhorst\, Shopify
DESCRIPTION:As observability systems grow\, evolving telemetry schemas is unavoidable. Even small\, backward-incompatible changes can break queries\, alerts\, duplicate data or harm dashboards. How can we adapt our observability platform to continuous change while preserving stability and performance?\n\nIn this talk\, we’ll explore how the OpenTelemetry Schema evolves and the challenges that come with it. We unpack pain points such as schema upgrades and downgrades (forward and backward compatibility)\, query-time aliasing and ingest-time translation and show how automating schema evolution can reduce maintenance overhead.\n\nWe demonstrate practical strategies to overcome these obstacles and walk through Shopify’s approach to safe\, automated schema evolution. Attendees will leave with practical ideas for approaching schema evolution in their own observability platforms\, reducing maintenance risks\, and keeping telemetry pipelines adaptable as they grow.
CATEGORIES:OBSERVABILITY DAY
LOCATION:Forum (Ground Floor)\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:f08d99854a37e5ab85aca6d68bb93a0f
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/f08d99854a37e5ab85aca6d68bb93a0f
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T094000Z
DTEND:20260323T100500Z
SUMMARY:Unpacking Your OTel Baggage - Dan Gomez Blanco\, New Relic & John Clark\, Skyscanner
DESCRIPTION:When one thinks about OpenTelemetry\, the first thoughts that come to mind are traces\, metrics\, logs\, or even profiles. Baggage\, as a signal\, doesn’t always get the recognition it deserves\, but those that have built solutions to propagate domain-specific information from service A to service G via custom headers have learnt that it’s a lot harder than it may initially seem!\n\nIn this talk\, we’ll demystify OTel Baggage as a W3C-standardised\, vendor-neutral specification for in-band context propagation. The official "carry-on" for your request context\, designed to travel with it everywhere (yes\, that pun was very much intended).\n\nWe'll explore the challenges it solves\, some common use cases\, and we'll deep-dive into how Skyscanner uses OTel Baggage to propagate Quality of Service (QoS) information. You'll see how this baggage\, carrying user priority\, is passed down the stack and used by Istio to make intelligent load-shedding decisions.\n\nCome claim the context you've been missing!
CATEGORIES:OBSERVABILITY DAY
LOCATION:E103-105 (1st Floor)\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:5f722e3544a5c8fdad5597f3e2bb2065
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/5f722e3544a5c8fdad5597f3e2bb2065
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T094000Z
DTEND:20260323T100500Z
SUMMARY:Trust\, Tampering\, and Transparency: What History Can Teach Us About Open Source Security - Lisa Tagliaferri\, Chainguard
DESCRIPTION:From encrypted letters and palimpsests to reproducible builds and digital attestations\, humans have long wrestled with how to prove authenticity\, preserve integrity\, and recover from tampering. As a medievalist turned software security practitioner\, I explore what centuries of information protection can teach us about today’s open source supply chain. This talk connects historical practices of trust and preservation to modern supply chain security. Using examples from early cryptography and material reuse\, we’ll examine frameworks like Sigstore\, SLSA\, Wolfi\, in-toto\, Tekton\, SBOMs\, and GUAC\, showing how they extend timeless concepts of verification and transparency into digital systems. By pairing the cultural lineage of security with today’s open tooling\, attendees will gain a deeper understanding of both the technical and human dimensions of trust.
CATEGORIES:OPEN SOURCE SECURITYCON
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room D\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:2af216a41896fe601bb56dac0c3e5fa3
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/2af216a41896fe601bb56dac0c3e5fa3
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T094000Z
DTEND:20260323T100500Z
SUMMARY:Creating an IDP for AI Engineering - Max Körbächer\, Liquid Reply GmbH
DESCRIPTION:What couldn't be more hyped than AI? But where is such hype\, some organizations struggle with the changes in their IT landscape and find new challenges in people\, processes and the technology.\nPlatform Engineering has proven its value in the past years\, allowing organizations to scale almost unlimitedly while enabling product development flow.\nSo\, why don't we bring our decades of experience in automation\, scaleability and reliability to AI? Well\, it is already there. Every tool needed to train\, deploy and use AI is cloud native. But it adds up to a completely new complexity on top of existing structures.\nThat's where the AIDP comes in. Leveraging the known\, integrating it with the existing solution\, to provide a unified entry point for organizations ramping up their AI Engineering capabilities. Think of it like Backstage\, just on steroids\, platform and end user-friendly\, with a dedication to be the one-stop shop for getting started with LLMs. It's the platform\, not the model.
CATEGORIES:PLATFORM ENGINEERING DAY
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room F\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:34be8b1fb3f2366fd7ef4d07a15166f4
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/34be8b1fb3f2366fd7ef4d07a15166f4
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T094000Z
DTEND:20260323T100500Z
SUMMARY:Scaling on Satisfaction: Automated Rollouts Driven by User Feedback - Thomas Vitale\, Systematic & Whitney Lee\, Datadog
DESCRIPTION:As the old saying goes\, “the customer is always right”. When it comes to GenAI\, the end users of our apps are indeed always right\, because we can’t fully trust an LLM on its own. What if we used a new mechanism to guide the routing and rollout of new application versions? How about user feedback? Imagine that: the more an app variant gets up-voted\, the more traffic is sent to it.\n\nIn this session\, Whitney and Thomas demo a platform that enables app developers to define success criteria for business operations involving GenAI\, and to capture users’ feedback using OpenTelemetry - including how to correlate it with other observability data. Then comes the twist. They’ll expand the platform using Flagger and Knative so that the users control the rollout and routing of new apps. And today\, YOU are the user\, the audience!\n\nYou’ll see how this technique can be applied beyond GenAI\, and take part in an interactive story that evolves and changes course in real time based on your feedback!
CATEGORIES:PLATFORM ENGINEERING DAY
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room G\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:bed94e0502ab3884b6420f2a8783e2b3
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/bed94e0502ab3884b6420f2a8783e2b3
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T094000Z
DTEND:20260323T100500Z
SUMMARY:Running Wasmtime in Hardware-Isolated Microenvironments - Danilo (Dan) Chiarlone\, Microsoft
DESCRIPTION:WebAssembly gives you a sandbox. VMs give you hardware isolation. Can you have both without destroying cold start times? For serverless workloads needing defense-in-depth\, traditional VMs are too slow. The answer is yes\, but only if you rethink what a VM needs to be.\nThis talk shows how to integrate hardware isolation with Wasm runtimes using two approaches. Hyperlight-Wasm strips away the OS: no kernel\, no system calls\, just memory and a CPU running no-std Wasmtime. Guest code communicates through the WebAssembly Component Model and WIT. Hyperlight-Nanvix pairs Hyperlight with a lightweight microkernel that gives you syscalls with kernel-level filtering and Rust standard library support.\nYou'll see architecture\, code\, and live demos for both. We'll cover how communication works with and without an OS\, what breaks and works in each model\, and performance tradeoffs. For anyone building platforms that run untrusted code\, working on Wasm tooling\, or curious about hardware isolation.
CATEGORIES:WASMCON
LOCATION:E106-108\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:ef00de7f3c6376c180c3a26daae079e3
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/ef00de7f3c6376c180c3a26daae079e3
