SUMMARY:Anatomy of a GitOps Engine: Understanding Your Sync - Alexandre Gaudreault\, Intuit
DESCRIPTION:Everyone clicks "sync"\, and just expects it to work. But what really happens under the hood? The Argo CD sync process is a powerful and complex dance\, and its heart - the GitOps Engine - has evolved.\n\nThis session dives deep into the anatomy of the engine responsible for making your desired state a reality. We will follow a single Application sync step-by-step\, from the initial sync operation request to the final "Synced" status. We'll demystify how different sync options\, resource hooks\, delete policies\, sync waves\, retries and more interact to build a precise execution plan. You'll see exactly how the engine orchestrates complex\, multi-stage deployments and how you can leverage these features to manage dependencies and control rollout order.\n\nIf you've ever wondered why a resource didn't sync the way you expected it to sync\, this talk is for you.
CATEGORIES:ARGOCON
LOCATION:G102-103\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:101492d1c5288886f84d1859e9b412c9
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/101492d1c5288886f84d1859e9b412c9
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T095000Z
DTEND:20260323T101500Z
SUMMARY:Empowering Autonomy: BYD's Journey Taming Million-Task Scale With Argo Workflows - Shuangkun Tian\, Alibaba Cloud & Zhang Bao\, BYD
DESCRIPTION:As BYD’s autonomous driving business scales rapidly\, our platform processes tens of millions of data records daily\, requiring efficient pipelines for cleaning\, labeling\, and repairing.\nWe migrated from Airflow to Kubernetes‑native Argo Workflows and built a system that manages 3\,000+ GPUs and runs over 1M data tasks per day.\nWe will share challenges and solutions from building the platform\, including:\n• GPU Utilization – Optimizing thousand‑GPU clusters for higher utilization and enabling multi‑tenant resource sharing.\n• High Concurrency – Sustaining millions of tasks with advanced concurrency control to boost throughput.\n• Extreme‑Scale Stability – Resolving scheduling challenges at 300k+ workflow scale\, such as informer update delays and controller memory spikes.\n• Community Contribution – Upstreaming fixes and scalability improvements to the Argo Workflows project.\nAttendees will gain strategies to orchestrate massive GPU‑intensive workflows and ensure stability at scale.
CATEGORIES:ARGOCON
LOCATION:Auditorium\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:b5927d5777ab947dd9232206afbd8b53
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/b5927d5777ab947dd9232206afbd8b53
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T100000Z
DTEND:20260323T102500Z
SUMMARY:Towards Better Canary Releases With Flagger and Gateway API - Sanskar Jaiswal\, Kong
DESCRIPTION:Canary releases are a great way to bring new software into production as they help identify any problems early and avert disasters. However\, existing strategies of weighted traffic shifting result in a bad user experience as requests randomly bounce between old and new versions on a per-request basis. It also does not produce great signal for developers. Can we have better Canary signals while improving end user experience?\n\nIn this talk\, Sanskar will demo a relatively new deployment strategy that modifies the Canary release workflow to work with user sessions rather than user requests. He will describe how session-based routing results in a more robust Canary deployment system\, allowing servers to be stateless while providing a consistent user experience. He will discuss how Gateway API plays a crucial role in enabling this feature and conclude the session with a demo showcasing this new strategy.
CATEGORIES:FLUXCON
LOCATION:Elicium 1\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:e5544fda42f9b8bae71fed7f024e8444
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/e5544fda42f9b8bae71fed7f024e8444
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T101500Z
DTEND:20260323T104000Z
SUMMARY:Agentic Backstage: How To Manage an AI Software Catalog - Sam Nixon\, Roadie
DESCRIPTION:AI and Backstage should be great friends\, but whether you’re working in a AI engineering team responsible for which models and architectures should be in use\, an application engineer just trying to connect to the the models and MCP servers you need for development\, or a Platform team trying to keep it all coherent and secure\, this information can be hard to access. When you layer on top autonomous agents making their own actions\, trying to maintain a useful Backstage instance in an AI world can be maddening.\n\nIn this talk\, we will share our experiences developing agents for Backstage\, modelling AI assets in the Catalog\, and what we think the role of Backstage will be as agents and AI tools become more prevalent. We’ll discuss how Backstage should be integral for AI-driven development and what we could change as a community to make sure of that future. Finally\, we’ll walk you through how to set up your own AI Catalog and how it can be extended both inside and outside the portal.
CATEGORIES:BACKSTAGECON
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room E\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:003554eeff4b4b752226b046f500e0a8
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/003554eeff4b4b752226b046f500e0a8
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T101500Z
DTEND:20260323T104000Z
SUMMARY:Expl(AI)n Like I’m 5: An Introduction To AI-Native Networking - Niranjan Shankar\, Microsoft & Ram Vennam\, Solo.io
DESCRIPTION:With new AI protocols\, acronyms\, and networking tools proliferating across the ecosystem\, it’s easy to feel overwhelmed. What do all these new terms actually mean\, and which ones are relevant to you? Do you really need to overhaul your networking infrastructure\, or are traditional solutions sufficient?\n\nIn this session\, we’ll explore the communications patterns behind core AI use-cases - training\, inference\, serving\, consumption\, and agentic interactions. You’ll learn the basics of key concepts and features\, like MCP\, A2A\, token-based rate-limiting\, prompt guarding\, etc\, and where they apply. We’ll then discuss where conventional networking technologies - service mesh\, CNIs\, gateways\, and L7 proxies - fit into this paradigm\, and when AI-aware implementations like the Gateway API Inference Extension are required for routing\, observing\, and securing GenAI workloads. Finally\, we’ll end with practical guidelines for taking these AI tools to production and integrating them into your stack.
CATEGORIES:CLOUD NATIVE AI + KUBEFLOW DAY
LOCATION:Hall 7 | Room B\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:5345aa49d6a9e6890d0dcb63022ca239
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/5345aa49d6a9e6890d0dcb63022ca239
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T101500Z
DTEND:20260323T104000Z
SUMMARY:Smarter Databases in Kubernetes: Applying AI for Query Optimization and Self-Tuning - Peter Zaitsev\, Percona
DESCRIPTION:As databases increasingly power real-time\, data-intensive applications\, managing their performance within Kubernetes environments presents new challenges. This session explores how artificial intelligence can transform traditional database management through adaptive query optimization and self-tuning capabilities.\n\nWe’ll discuss practical approaches for integrating AI and machine learning models into cloud-native database platforms to analyze workloads\, detect inefficiencies\, and automatically adjust parameters such as indexing\, caching\, and resource allocation. The talk will highlight emerging patterns behind “self-driving” databases\, systems that learn from historical performance data to improve query efficiency and response times continuously.\n\nAttendees will gain actionable insights into building smarter\, autonomous database systems that leverage AI to optimize performance\, reduce operational overhead\, and enhance scalability across Kubernetes clusters.
CATEGORIES:CLOUD NATIVE AI + KUBEFLOW DAY
LOCATION:Hall 7 | Room C\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:66edd06df2221c66a4cb73ffc8a28c19
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/66edd06df2221c66a4cb73ffc8a28c19
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T101500Z
DTEND:20260323T104000Z
SUMMARY:From YANG To YAML: How We Tamed the 5G Configuration Beast - Joel Studler\, Swisscom & Peter Wörndle\, Ericsson
DESCRIPTION:Discover our breakthrough results from a unique telco operator-vendor collaboration on cloud-native 5G configuration management!\n\nWe’ll demonstrate our declarative GitOps solution using KRM and Kubernetes operators that simplifies complex YANG configurations for cloud-native network functions. Learn how combining telco operator knowledge with vendor expertise overcame practical cloud-native telco transformation challenges.\n\nOur results showcase successful integration of a CNF with KRO\, SDCIO\, and dynamic IPAM hydration - proving operators and vendors can co-innovate effectively within the CNCF ecosystem. We’ll share our lessons learned\, architectural decisions\, and proven patterns for making 5G infrastructure truly cloud-native.\n\nJoin us to explore this collaborative model that accelerates industry adoption and aligns perfectly with CNCF’s mission!
CATEGORIES:CLOUD NATIVE TELCO DAY
LOCATION:G104-105\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:6e1809ebbd87f2f888eb8d0d5e08b069
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/6e1809ebbd87f2f888eb8d0d5e08b069
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T101500Z
DTEND:20260323T104000Z
SUMMARY:Bridging the Gap Between Human and Workload Identity: SPIFFE Support in Keycloak - Arndt Schwenkschuster\, Defakto Security & Dmitry Telegin\, Backbase UK
DESCRIPTION:Human identity has been around for a while. In the beginning\, authentication was just a simple password. With second-factor authentication and lately passkeys this has become much more secure but there’s always a factor of customer experience. How many factors can you prompt until the user stops?\n\nThis is different with workloads. They will endlessly provide authentication factors and won’t complain. This is great for security and building “multi-factor authentication” for workloads is easy. Keycloak supports multiple client authentication methods but many are difficult to deploy. Most of the time\, simple client secret authentication is chosen. Others require key pairs and issuing self-signed JSON Web Tokens.\n\nSince Keycloak 26.4\, secure client authentication is easier than ever. Support for SPIFFE identities as a means of client authentication has been added. No more client secrets or difficult-to-deploy secret keys. You can simply use a SPIFFE identity obtained at runtime.
CATEGORIES:KEYCLOAKCON
LOCATION:Hall 7 | Room A\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:e1ce2513d2490c81d317ba7e6e886618
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/e1ce2513d2490c81d317ba7e6e886618
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T101500Z
DTEND:20260323T104000Z
SUMMARY:Proving Trust: Signed Supply Chains and Verifiable Deployments at the Edge - Sheldon Lo-A-Njoe\, Spectro Cloud & Nicolas Ferrao\, Airbus Defence and Space
DESCRIPTION:As Kubernetes expands beyond the cloud into disconnected and resource-constrained environments\, integrity must be proven\, not assumed.\nThis session presents a reproducible framework for verifiable software supply chains\, combining SLSA-compliant builds\, signed artefacts\, and GitOps automation.\nUsing open-source tools such as cosign\, SignServer\, and Flux/ArgoCD\, we'll show how hardware-backed keys (eg YubiKeys) can anchor cryptographic trust directly into CI/CD workflows.\nAttendees will learn how to achieve continuous attestation from build to deployment\, ensuring reproducible\, signed\, and verifiable workloads\, anywhere Kubernetes runs.
CATEGORIES:KUBERNETES ON EDGE DAY
LOCATION:Emerald Room\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:5c54ffa17ad8aed52d36e466b14ee5cd
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/5c54ffa17ad8aed52d36e466b14ee5cd
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T101500Z
DTEND:20260323T104000Z
SUMMARY:How to Use the OpenTelemetry Demo and Why It Matters - Juliano Costa\, Datadog
DESCRIPTION:If you’ve walked by any observability vendor booth at KubeCon in the past couple of years\, chances are you’ve seen the OpenTelemetry Demo in action — it’s everywhere. The “Astronomy Shop\,” better known as the OpenTelemetry Demo\, is more than a collection of microservices — it’s where OpenTelemetry proves itself in action. Widely used by vendors across the ecosystem\, it showcases how to apply OpenTelemetry in a real-world scenario: from instrumenting applications to configuring the OpenTelemetry Collector to tie everything together.\n\nBut the Demo isn’t just for vendors. Whether you’re a newcomer exploring OpenTelemetry for the first time\, a SIG maintainer\, or an experienced user evaluating an observability backend migration\, the Demo can make your life easier and help you do your job better.\n\nJoin this talk to discover how the OpenTelemetry Demo can empower you by providing the tools and data you need to leverage OpenTelemetry to its full potential!\n\n
CATEGORIES:OBSERVABILITY DAY
LOCATION:E103-105 (1st Floor)\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:2174c447f4b9fdaea23f3807af8780ee
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/2174c447f4b9fdaea23f3807af8780ee
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T101500Z
DTEND:20260323T104000Z
SUMMARY:Observability at the Edge: State of OpenTelemetry in Kubernetes Ingress Controllers - Kasper Borg Nissen\, Dash0
DESCRIPTION:Ingress controllers are the front door to your Kubernetes cluster\, but for many they remain a blind spot. Every request passes through ingress\, making it the natural starting point of distributed traces. If you only instrument downstream services\, you miss the first span: TLS negotiation\, routing decisions\, or middleware delays. Without these\, your observability story is incomplete.\n\nWe'll explore the current state of observability across the most widely adopted ingress controllers\, showing where OpenTelemetry support is strong\, and where gaps remain. We will cover why tracing at the edge is critical\, how to combine it with metrics and logs\, and how to achieve correlation across signals\, e.g. by using the OpenTelemetry Collector to enrich and link telemetry. Through practical insights and live demos\, We’ll compare controllers\, show how to turn ingress from a black box into the root of your distributed traces\, and highlight what this means for the future of observability in Kubernetes.
CATEGORIES:OBSERVABILITY DAY
LOCATION:Forum (Ground Floor)\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:57fd47a711bb3608b6d30d42a9289e72
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/57fd47a711bb3608b6d30d42a9289e72
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T101500Z
DTEND:20260323T104000Z
SUMMARY:Upstream Collaboration for the Win (of the CRA)! - Georg Kunz & Jan Melen\, Ericsson Software Technology
DESCRIPTION:In this talk\, Georg and Jan argue that software vendors with a strong upstream engagement will have a significantly easier time meeting EU Cyber Resilience Act (CRA) obligations due to their network of developers across upstream projects\, due to a better insight into projects health\, and due to their generally better capability to eliminate vulnerabilities in their upstream dependencies.\n\nGeorg will show how an OSPO can lead the necessary cultural change within a company and rally industry partners in the OpenSSF around the common cause of improving the upstream security posture. Jan will share how his team has successfully contributed security fixes to more than half of the CNCF projects. In combination\, this talk and the examples presented make a strong case for increased upstream engagement by software vendors\, thereby directly benefiting and strengthening the ecosystem.
CATEGORIES:OPEN SOURCE SECURITYCON
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room D\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:bbed78b4c62fba72b01a07feacdda377
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/bbed78b4c62fba72b01a07feacdda377
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T101500Z
DTEND:20260323T104000Z
SUMMARY:How To Play Support for a Platform Team - Awar Abdulkarim & Roberth Strand\, Sopra Steria
DESCRIPTION:Modern platform engineering is often described in terms of development\, automation\, and infrastructure - ultimately creating a golden path. What then about the people paving and walking that golden path? This talk explores what it truly means to “play support” for a platform team: enabling others to build\, ship\, and innovate faster without becoming a bottleneck. Playing support involves having the meetings no one else wants\, creating the solutions no one can be asked to create. Drawing on lessons from large-scale platform initiatives at Bane NOR\, we’ll discuss how internal platforms evolve from service providers to trusted partners by utilising their support. Attendees will gain practical insights on fostering alignment across platform teams\, balancing autonomy with governance\, and how this is achieved on a daily basis.
CATEGORIES:PLATFORM ENGINEERING DAY
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room F\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:a74c2fc0e3305737bea6bb62a01b8887
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/a74c2fc0e3305737bea6bb62a01b8887
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T101500Z
DTEND:20260323T104000Z
SUMMARY:Promotion Failed: How (Not) To Stage Your (Kubernetes) Platform - Nicolai Ort\, ODIT.Services
DESCRIPTION:Creating a Kubernetes platform is one thing — getting teams to trust and adopt it is another.\nWhen it’s time for an upgrade\, the margin for error suddenly feels razor-thin. A staging environment sounds like the obvious answer to prevent disruptions and keep your users' trust\, but how do you make sure what passes staging truly reaches - and works - in production?\n\nIn this talk\, we’ll explore several strategies for building and promoting staged environments\, from simple replication to declarative pipelines and automated diffing.\nThrough the lens of a Kubernetes-as-a-Service platform\, you’ll gain practical insight and tipps on designing a promotion process that fits your platform’s maturity and scale.
CATEGORIES:PLATFORM ENGINEERING DAY
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room G\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:b49443e5846fbd0aca9aa3be7163d7e5
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/b49443e5846fbd0aca9aa3be7163d7e5
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T101500Z
DTEND:20260323T104000Z
SUMMARY:GraalVM: WebAssembly for the JVM Ecosystem - Fabio Niephaus & Shaun Smith\, Oracle
DESCRIPTION:The JVM is one of the world’s most widely used programming platforms\, yet it’s rarely mentioned in conjunction with WebAssembly—until now! GraalVM brings Wasm to the JVM ecosystem with two projects: the GraalWasm runtime\, and GraalVM Web Image\, a new JVM bytecode-to-Wasm compiler.\n\nThis session introduces GraalWasm\, an embeddable Wasm runtime with excellent tooling and exceptional performance thanks to the optimizing Graal JIT compiler. We'll demo and debug a Rust library\, compiled to Wasm\, and embedded in a Spring Boot microservice.\n\nWe’ll also present GraalVM Web Image which can compile JVM applications into efficient Wasm modules that start up fast and run in the browser\, on mobile\, and in the cloud. We’ll explain how it works\, highlight practical use cases\, demo end-to-end workflows\, and discuss current limitations and what’s next.\n\nIf you’re interested in bringing Wasm to the legions of independent and enterprise JVM developers who have yet to embrace it\, this session is for you!
CATEGORIES:WASMCON
LOCATION:E106-108\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:c021be5e5c3539f54f6761929644ea9c
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/c021be5e5c3539f54f6761929644ea9c
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T102500Z
DTEND:20260323T105000Z
SUMMARY:Beyond Argo Rollouts: Boosting Developer Experience With Intelligent AIOps - Carlos Sanchez\, Adobe & Kevin Dubois\, IBM
DESCRIPTION:Software rollouts can be painful and complex. Tools like Argo Rollouts provide a robust foundation to ease the pain\, but with Cloud Native AI we can revolutionize the developer experience around it. This session explores elevating your release process by:\n\n* Integrating Agentic AI: Analyze rollout failures using AI agents.\n* Leveraging Models Deployed on Kubernetes: Utilize scalable AI models that are in your control.\n* Employing Intelligent Coding Agents: These cloud-based agents can make code corrections based on the failure analysis and create automated PRs\, and timely notifications.\n* Embracing Human-in-the-Loop Oversight: Provide developers with confidence and control by allowing them to review and course correct if needed.\n\nThis strategic combination of Cloud Native tools leads to significantly reduced Mean Time To Recovery (MTTR) and a more resilient\, productive developer experience. Join us to discover the future of seamless software delivery.
CATEGORIES:ARGOCON
LOCATION:G102-103\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:c1a62f70ee3dc87448b7e84650c2b7b0
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/c1a62f70ee3dc87448b7e84650c2b7b0
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T102500Z
DTEND:20260323T105000Z
SUMMARY:Don't Do What Donny Don't Does: The 10 Dos and 500 Don’ts of Workflows Success - Tim Collins\, Pipekit & Becky Pauley\, Tailscale
DESCRIPTION:Think your Argo Workflows cluster is production-ready just because it runs? Think again! While getting up and running takes no time at all\, the real operational complexity happens when Day 2 Operations kick in. That’s when subtle misconfigurations\, scaling challenges\, and security gaps emerge\, threatening reliability and uptime. Day 2 Operations mean grappling with real-world issues: debugging Workflow failures\, enforcing security best practices\, and avoiding performance bottlenecks.\n\nJoin us for a deep dive into the top pitfalls observed in production. Drawing from real customer incidents\, we’ll unpack the most frequent missteps and their consequences.\n\nWhether you're running a handful of Workflows or planning to scale to enterprise volumes\, this talk will transform your understanding of what it takes to run Argo Workflows reliably. Expect actionable guidance\, hard-won lessons\, and field-proven solutions you can put to work immediately. No theory. Just real ops\, real outcomes.
CATEGORIES:ARGOCON
LOCATION:Auditorium\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:42448da580be3e0bcacf17e6008c2a4e
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/42448da580be3e0bcacf17e6008c2a4e
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T103000Z
DTEND:20260323T105500Z
SUMMARY:Talking to Your Cluster: Conversational GitOps with Flux MCP - William Rizzo\, Mirantis
DESCRIPTION:The Flux project is pioneering a new era\, evolving GitOps from simple deployment automation into an intelligent operations platform. With the Flux MCP Server and integrated AI workflows\, Platform Engineering teams\, SRE and Developers can gain new operational superpowers. This session explores how AI-assisted GitOps transforms daily work by connecting conversational interfaces to Flux\, enabling instant health insights\, clearer understanding of delivery pipelines\, and rapid detection of configuration drift across clusters. We’ll highlight how AI accelerates incident response\, generates architecture documentation on demand\, and supports secure developer self-service. Finally\, we’ll preview how this model paves the way for advanced capabilities like staged multi-cluster rollouts\, predictive troubleshooting\, and policy-driven automation.
CATEGORIES:FLUXCON
LOCATION:Elicium 1\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:6f3e90416ca71f09ec67f73c36a2b6de
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/6f3e90416ca71f09ec67f73c36a2b6de
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T104500Z
DTEND:20260323T105500Z
SUMMARY:⚡Lightning Talk: Effortlessly Integrating Keycloak Authentication To Your MCP Servers - Lin Sun\, Solo.io
DESCRIPTION:You have built your first MCP server and tested it with the MCP Inspector\, but it currently runs over stdio or streamable HTTP without HTTPS. Now you are asking yourself: should you rewrite your server to add authentication and authorization\, or is there a smarter approach? And what happens when you scale to multiple MCP servers? Do you really need to modify each one?\n\nIn this demo-driven session\, Lin first shows the "hard way": modifying MCP server code\, rebuilding\, and redeploying to add authentication. After that\, she introduces a much simpler method by offloading authentication to Keycloak through an MCP gateway\, which allows you to secure your servers without changing or redeploying them.
CATEGORIES:KEYCLOAKCON
LOCATION:Hall 7 | Room A\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:fd8e7a1f35e4e057cbbbbb82eb4e6f75
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/fd8e7a1f35e4e057cbbbbb82eb4e6f75
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T104500Z
DTEND:20260323T111000Z
SUMMARY:Building Unified Global Load Balancing for the Edge With k8gb -Bradley Andersen\, k8gb & Yury Tsarev\, Upbound
DESCRIPTION:As Kubernetes expands to hundreds or thousands of edge locations across retail\, telecom\, and industrial sites\, traditional GSLB tools fall short. Proprietary\, data-center-centric systems are hard to run where connectivity is intermittent\, autonomy is needed\, and latency targets are strict. \n \nThis session demonstrates how k8gb\, a CNCF Sandbox project\, brings global load balancing into the Kubernetes model. Using a simple CRD and GitOps workflow\, k8gb leverages DNS as a reliable\, standards-based mechanism while adding Kubernetes-native automation and observability. The speaker shows patterns such as nearest-edge routing\, traffic spillover\, and graceful degradation\, and explains how k8gb detects and reports inconsistent DNS state during partitions so operators can restore a consistent global view once connectivity returns. \n \nAttendees will take away practical patterns for health-based failover\, geo-aware routing\, and disaster recovery at the edge.
CATEGORIES:KUBERNETES ON EDGE DAY
LOCATION:Emerald Room\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:040de4548e2635dcd3fa72cc15836bc4
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/040de4548e2635dcd3fa72cc15836bc4
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T104500Z
DTEND:20260323T111000Z
SUMMARY:Split Rendering TV Applications Using WASM - Timothy Pearce & Rajiv Ramdhany\, BBC
DESCRIPTION:Public Service Broadcasters have a remit to provide universal access to their content. This poses a unique technical challenge when developing Video Streaming Applications which have to run on devices like Smart TVs\, which often have constrained hardware. Additionally\, audiences are expecting more from applications such as richer user interfaces with smooth animations and more interaction\, which some devices struggle with.\n\nWe have been investigating how to use WebAssembly to author flexible applications which can offload operations such as UI rendering and animation from client devices to edge compute and the cloud. Richer animations and interactions impose additional performance constraints. We have looked at whether offloading UI-rendering delivers the required quality of experience. Offloading rendering WASM modules is simplified if these are truly portable. We describe our approach to try to make UI-component rendering with WASM modules portable\, highlight the challenges and describe the mechanisms to stream the rendered UIs at low-latency to the client.
CATEGORIES:WASMCON
LOCATION:E106-108\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:a600589fde163d3f92071a98d02680ad
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/a600589fde163d3f92071a98d02680ad
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T105000Z
DTEND:20260323T112500Z
SUMMARY:Panel: Building a Healthy Backstage Plugins Ecosystem - Paul Schultz & Hope Hadfield\, Red Hat; Heikki Hellgren\, OP Financial Group; Peter Macdonald\, VodafoneZiggo; Aramis Sennyey\, DoorDash
DESCRIPTION:Backstage’s plugin ecosystem is a key draw for the Backstage product\, enabling teams to extend the platform to meet their own needs. But as the ecosystem matures across both the core and Community Plugins repository\, new challenges emerge around sustainability\, quality\, and governance. This panel brings together maintainers and contributors from across the Backstage community to explore what it means to build and maintain healthy plugins in this evolving landscape. We’ll dig into questions like:\n\nWhat’s the biggest barrier for a new contributor\, and how can we make that experience smoother?\nHow can we balance innovation and its adoption (i.e. the new frontend system) with the need for quality and efficient plugin maintenance?\nWhat lessons can we draw from how different repositories handle ownership\, testing\, and dependency management\, and where should those practices converge?\n\nThis discussion will map out where Backstage’s plugin ecosystem stands today\, and where it needs to go next.
CATEGORIES:BACKSTAGECON
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room E\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
