SUMMARY:Panel: Routing Intelligence Vs Traffic Control: Architectural Tradeoffs for AI Inference in Gateway API - Abdullah Gharaibeh\, Google; Morgan Foster\, Red Hat; Eitan Yarmush\, Solo.io; Dan Sun\, Bloomberg
DESCRIPTION:As AI inference workloads become the norm in Kubernetes\, the Gateway API Inference Extension (GAIE) faced a pivotal architectural question: should request scheduling act as a "consultant" via an external processing filter or become a full-fledged Service in the traffic path?\nThis panel brings together maintainers and practitioners to explore two models for routing AI inference. GAIE uses external processing to make scheduling decisions without proxying traffic - an unconventional but deliberate choice that prioritizes simplicity and performance. An alternative would place the scheduler directly in the data path as a next-hop Service\, aligning with Gateway API norms.\nThis discussion isn’t just theoretical - the architecture shapes what GAIE can do and how it integrates with Gateway API. Attendees will leave with a clear decision framework for designing GW API extensions\, and a deeper understanding of how architectural choices impact performance\, complexity\, and ecosystem alignment.
CATEGORIES:CLOUD NATIVE AI + KUBEFLOW DAY
LOCATION:Hall 7 | Room B\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:fe6eb513309d6e67598f511c801077ff
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/fe6eb513309d6e67598f511c801077ff
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T114500Z
DTEND:20260323T122000Z
SUMMARY:Panel: The Spec-tacular Game Show V2 - Alex Boten & Tyler Helmuth\, Honeycomb; Adriana Villela\, Dynatrace; Pablo Baeyens\, Datadog; Marylia Gutierrez\, Grafana Labs
DESCRIPTION:From OTLP to OTTL\, engineers are excited about a lot of things. But there is one thing that excites them above all else and that is correcting people. Welcome to the second installment of “The Spec-tacular Game Show”.\n\nIn this fun game show our panelists will be given incorrect statements about the OpenTelemetry Specification or Semantic Conventions. The panelists will buzz in\, identify what’s wrong\, and state the correction. If none of the panelists know the answer the audience will get a chance to answer to steal the point. The panelist (or audience) with the most points wins!\n\nAfter each question we will discuss why the specification is the way it is and highlight how it produces the production-quality telemetry you know and love. Join us for a fun\, relaxing\, (snarky) panel about everyone’s favorite part of Otel!
CATEGORIES:OBSERVABILITY DAY
LOCATION:Forum (Ground Floor)\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:deb2e3c9e49d5df3425aacace14ed71d
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/deb2e3c9e49d5df3425aacace14ed71d
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T114500Z
DTEND:20260323T121000Z
SUMMARY:The Day 2 Hangover: What To Do After the Platform Party Ends - Cat Morris\, Syntasso & Nitish Malhotra\, Veeam Software
DESCRIPTION:Often\, new platform teams start building for day 1 concerns: new apps\, experiments\, and cool tech. Everyone is excited by shiny new self-service platforms. But success can be short-lived. When building platforms\, it's easy to think of just creating things - a platform party! But as time goes by\, it is hard to ignore the day 2 hangover.\nAt Veeam\, a global company known for its backup and recovery software\, its platform-building efforts were so prolific that it had hundreds of components that app teams had to combine. The day 1 experience was amazing\, but the day 2 concerns had been ignored. Operating\, maintaining\, and demonstrating the platform's value became increasingly challenging.\nIn this talk\, Nitish and Cat share how the team introduced platform orchestration patterns to simplify operations and reduce maintenance overhead. Without a complete rebuild\, the team significantly reduced the cost to manage platform resources and freed up time to deliver real business value.
CATEGORIES:PLATFORM ENGINEERING DAY
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room G\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:12cb1889a4529714799d86cd92ef46ea
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/12cb1889a4529714799d86cd92ef46ea
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T114500Z
DTEND:20260323T121000Z
SUMMARY:We Broke Free From Cloud-Managed Kubernetes: Now What? - Kārlis Akots Gribulis & Per Hedegaard Christiansen\, Saxo Bank
DESCRIPTION:Have you ever wondered what happens after moving from cloud-managed Kubernetes to self-hosted clusters? One year into Saxo Bank’s journey\, we’re sharing the full story: what worked\, what surprised us\, and what we would do differently.\n\nIn this talk\, you’ll hear about:\n- Did things just work?\n- Was it possible to migrate large-scale workloads?\n- Did we actually manage to get 80% cost reduction?\n- Lessons learned around resilience\, automation\, and lifecycle management with kubeadm + Cluster API.\n\nAttendees will leave with a realistic understanding of the trade-offs\, risks\, and benefits of self-hosted Kubernetes at scale\, plus actionable insights for planning and operating their own clusters.
CATEGORIES:PLATFORM ENGINEERING DAY
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room F\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:e5c0eef76e6b977bc53bf9e86db53519
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/e5c0eef76e6b977bc53bf9e86db53519
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T115000Z
DTEND:20260323T122500Z
SUMMARY:Panel: Building a GitOps Culture - Dan Garfield & Revital Barletz\, Octopus Deploy; Antonela Cukurin\, Novo Nordisk & Gabriel Quennesson\, Michelin
DESCRIPTION:We spend 90% of our time talking about GitOps from a technical perspective but that is not where organizations struggle. Instead\, they stall on building a GitOps Culture. In many ways\, a GitOps Culture is a realization of DevOps culture. Enabling self-service\, independence of action and ownership\, and clean audit trails are part of GitOps culture.\n\nArgo CD and Argo Rollouts are largely unopinionated about culture\, but most implementation decisions are downstream of culture. In this panel\, we’ll hear from end users and experts alike about how to build a culture that enables GitOps and some of the technical hallmarks that show you’re on the right path.
CATEGORIES:ARGOCON
LOCATION:G102-103\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:968527783cd461421a2bbb4043e4a5c3
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/968527783cd461421a2bbb4043e4a5c3
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T115000Z
DTEND:20260323T122500Z
SUMMARY:Panel: From Signals To Safety Nets: Self-Healing Progressive Delivery With Argo Rollouts - Anastasiia Gubska\, Chase UK; Julia Furst Morgado\, Dash0; Joe Fuller\, Buoyant
DESCRIPTION:What if your deployment pipeline could sense failure and heal itself before users notice?\n\nIn this session\, we show how to build self-healing progressive delivery pipelines using Argo Rollouts powered by real-time observability signals. Integrating Prometheus\, OpenTelemetry\, and Linkerd\, we transform rollouts from time-based experiments into signal-driven systems that auto-react to performance degradation.\n\nSee how:\n- A canary detects rising latency and auto-rolls back early before wider exposure\n- Error spikes trigger KEDA-based scaling and pause Rollouts until stable\n- Service-mesh insights feed AnalysisTemplates for closed-loop remediation\n\nWhile we use specific tools\, the patterns are universal: any mesh\, any metrics stack\, any automation framework. You’ll take home templates\, blueprints\, and decision frameworks that make Argo Rollouts the control plane for resilience\, ushering in the next phase of progressive delivery: Automated Resilience Engineering.
CATEGORIES:ARGOCON
LOCATION:Auditorium\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:886b9dcea903070b62b68b5800e26394
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/886b9dcea903070b62b68b5800e26394
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T115500Z
DTEND:20260323T122000Z
SUMMARY:Scaling Telemetry To Terabytes: Applying Google's Principles To OpenTelemetry With OpAMP - Raphael Menderico\, Google
DESCRIPTION:This talk addresses the challenges of operating Google's monitoring systems at scale\, handling terabytes of telemetry data and preventing overload from diverse workloads. We'll explore how Google's internal client library and Monarch\, its planet-scale time-series database\, work together for cost-effective data collection. Key principles include a distributed push model\, dynamic client-side data reduction\, centralized retention\, and periodic metric analysis. The session will then bridge these concepts to the open-source world\, discussing our work with OpenTelemetry's OpAMP protocol to achieve similar scalable and efficient telemetry collection. Attendees will gain insights into adapting these principles for cost savings and learn about our collaboration with the OpAMP SIG to benefit the broader community.
CATEGORIES:OBSERVABILITY DAY
LOCATION:E103-105 (1st Floor)\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:ff6aa15a273024714c4d25d971f50640
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/ff6aa15a273024714c4d25d971f50640
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T122000Z
DTEND:20260323T124500Z
SUMMARY:A Practical Guide To Inner Sourcing Your IDP - Lian Li\, lianmakesthings
DESCRIPTION:Bridging the gap between developers and platform teams is hard.\nScattered documentation\, fragmented language and hidden knowledge leave developers frustrated\, while platform teams struggle to understand what devs really need. Treating platforms as products is a start\, but treating them like open source projects unlocks real collaboration\, allowing developers to contribute and maintain features.\nIn my roles as Developer Advocate and platform engineer\, I have years of experience working with highly bureaucratic organisations helping to improve developer experience and adoption.\nIn this talk\, I’ll share concrete steps to identify contribution opportunities\, set up maintainable processes\, and measure engagement. You’ll leave inspired with ideas to boost adoption\, reduce friction\, and turn your platform into a collaborative\, thriving ecosystem.
CATEGORIES:PLATFORM ENGINEERING DAY
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room G\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:9a39cccd52f812db850137e996644d19
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/9a39cccd52f812db850137e996644d19
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T122000Z
DTEND:20260323T124500Z
SUMMARY:Overwhelmed by Scale: How Product Thinking Fixes Platform Teams - Dominik Schmidle\, giantswarm.io
DESCRIPTION:Your platform team started small. You automated Kubernetes cluster provisioning with some Terraform scripts\, added useful services\, teams adopted your platform. Success! Then reality hit: drowning in tickets\, firefighting\, endless upgrades. Your small team serves hundreds of developers with no time for strategic work. Leadership sees your platform as a cost center with unclear ROI.\n\nThis pattern repeats everywhere. Platform teams get trapped building what's requested\, reacting to fires\, unable to say no or think strategically. The problem: treating platforms as service desks instead of products.\n\nDrawing from workshops with dozens of organizations\, this talk shows how product thinking breaks the cycle. You'll learn to move from firefighting to strategic ownership through vision-driven roadmaps\, prioritization enabling saying no\, and value communication shifting platforms from cost centers to strategic assets\, including practical patterns for restructuring teams.
CATEGORIES:PLATFORM ENGINEERING DAY
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room F\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
