BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T123000Z
DTEND:20260323T125500Z
SUMMARY:Baby Sitting Your AI Models in Production? STOP! - Ram Iyengar\, Linux Foundation
DESCRIPTION:AI in production is broken. They're as fussy\, as can be. The number of personas involved in making an AI model ready for production is high\, which makes MLOps an order of magnitude more complicated compared to DevOps.\n\nThis talk introduces a streamlined\, standardized workflow to take the manual effort out of MLOps packaging & deployment.\n\nThe first step is ModelPack\, a sandbox project under the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF). It provides a standard\, open-source way to organize all the files that make up a machine learning model.\n\nWe will introduce ModelKit\, which is a directory structure that logically groups all the previously dispersed artifacts into a single\, cohesive package. The final deployment artifact will automate the process of building a runnable\, OCI-compliant container image.\n\nThe final step of deployment becomes rudimentary\, as the image is available on any container registry.
CATEGORIES:CLOUD NATIVE AI + KUBEFLOW DAY
LOCATION:Hall 7 | Room B\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:e1da258c984db793f69fb1701f5d74a0
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/e1da258c984db793f69fb1701f5d74a0
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T123000Z
DTEND:20260323T125500Z
SUMMARY:Kubeflow Trainer Observability: Real-Time Progress Tracking for Reliable ML Training on Kubernetes - Abhijeet Dhumal & Rob Bell\, Red Hat
DESCRIPTION:Without observability\, training is just expensive guesswork.\n\nImagine a hyperparameter search across 50 configurations—16 GPUs for 8 hours each—consumes 6\,400 GPU-hours at $25\,600. Without real-time metrics\, underperforming configs burn resources. Platform teams can't distinguish converging TrainJobs from diverging ones. Algorithms like Hyperband reduce costs through early stopping\, but can't function without real-time training metrics from distributed jobs.\n\nIn this session\, we'll show how Kubeflow Trainer v2's native observability unlocks Katib's full potential. We'll demonstrate how training metrics flow into TrainJob status through the Kubernetes API—no code instrumentation\, no MLflow servers\, no TensorBoard infrastructure. We'll show how to query progress with kubectl. We'll demonstrate Katib's Hyperband watching TrainJob eval metrics and terminating underperforming trials immediately\, delivering 5-10x cost reduction.\n\nWith native observability\, make every GPU-hour count!
CATEGORIES:CLOUD NATIVE AI + KUBEFLOW DAY
LOCATION:Hall 7 | Room C\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:a5bc7cd21fe478177ca59cbc632bd478
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/a5bc7cd21fe478177ca59cbc632bd478
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T123000Z
DTEND:20260323T125500Z
SUMMARY:Teaching Machines To Debug Machines: Building an AI-Powered RCA Agent for Sylva-Core - Mihai Zaharia & Vladimir Braquet\, Orange
DESCRIPTION:In modern cloud-native environments\, operators face hundreds of alerts daily from Kubernetes clusters\, network functions\, and infrastructure components. Traditional approaches require manual investigation\, correlation across multiple tools\, and\, let's face it\, tribal knowledge that doesn't quite scale well.\n\nThis talk focuses on our journey building an RCA agent that autonomously investigates and tries to get the root cause of alerts in a Kubernetes-based telco cloud environment.\nAs the base infrastructure we used `sylva-core` to deploy our k8s clusters and manage the monitoring stack.\n\nWe'll go through the steps that we took to build this \, focusing on:\n- Choosing the right framework .\n- Prompt engineering and design patterns.\n- Model Context Protocol\n- Memory systems\n\nWe'll walk through real examples of the agent investigating Kubernetes pod failures\, correlating them with similar past incidents\, and providing actionable RCA without human intervention.
CATEGORIES:CLOUD NATIVE TELCO DAY
LOCATION:G104-105\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:c46301fdada8cd345e8135dd10ed5a45
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/c46301fdada8cd345e8135dd10ed5a45
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T123000Z
DTEND:20260323T125500Z
SUMMARY:Accelerating Science\, Decelerating Carbon: Sustainable Computing at CERN - Laura Llinares & Amine Lahouel\, CERN
DESCRIPTION:At CERN\, where particle physics meets cloud-native scale\, workloads are increasingly powered by GPUs and accelerators for simulation and machine learning. These advances are incredible for science—but they raise new questions around efficiency\, energy\, and carbon impact.\n\nWe’ll share how we’re building a metrics-driven framework—rooted in Kubernetes and CNCF tooling—to measure and improve workload efficiency across on-prem and cloud environments. By defining a shared set of metrics for cost and carbon reporting\, we’re turning observability data into actionable insights for sustainable computing.\n\nYou’ll see how real HEP workloads use this framework to visualize performance\, uncover inefficiencies\, and guide smarter infrastructure decisions. The goal: empower every team to understand the environmental footprint of their cloud-native applications—and make sustainability a first-class metric in our stacks.
CATEGORIES:OBSERVABILITY DAY
LOCATION:E103-105 (1st Floor)\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:9f03447d9faeddb78a8c803643529206
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/9f03447d9faeddb78a8c803643529206
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T123000Z
DTEND:20260323T125500Z
SUMMARY:To Make an SLO\, First You Must Invent the Universe: OpenTelemetry Collection From Scratch - Cail Young\, Octopus Deploy
DESCRIPTION:In 2025\, a team at Octopus Deploy was tasked with building out a multi-region\, highly-available\, autoscaling OpenTelemetry-based telemetry processing platform. We'd never had something like this before\, and didn't have many documented examples to work from.\n\nThis case study aims to make public the moving parts required to deliver a brand new telemetry pipeline based on OpenTelemetry Collector and Kubernetes\, and will examine the many tradeoffs and misadventures we went on while building it out.
CATEGORIES:OBSERVABILITY DAY
LOCATION:Forum (Ground Floor)\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:e5efcddc83fec0a47c61670a266b0596
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/e5efcddc83fec0a47c61670a266b0596
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T123000Z
DTEND:20260323T125500Z
SUMMARY:Zero Privilege Architecture - 3 Years Onward - Thijs Ebbers & Tadeo Sanchez\, ING
DESCRIPTION:At KubeCon EU 2023 in Amsterdam ING revealed its "Zero Privilege Architecture" on which its on premise ING Container Hosting Platform ("ICHP") is based.\n\nIn this Talk we'll do a short recap of that architecture model and analyze some of the major security events of the past 3 years and how these did (not) impact us.\nThis by explaining which aspects/controls of this architecture prevented or mitigated the threat(s) at hand.\n\nWe hope to inspire the audience to think beyond the traditional security paradigm (shipping/installing insecure software\, overprovisioning of privileges\, dealing with false positives\, praying for a patch for detected vulnerabilities to appear soon and work like a maniac to try to get all available patches applied timely....\, ) and show there is a feasible alternative (and yes\, that does takes effort to achieve...).\n\nAnd we'll give some more detailed insights in how "Zero Privilege Architecture" actually works under the hood in ING.\n\nThis talk is 100% AI free \;-)
CATEGORIES:OPEN SOURCE SECURITYCON
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room D\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:e81c634391e976f11e2f93f514b28111
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/e81c634391e976f11e2f93f514b28111
