DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T123500Z
DTEND:20260323T125500Z
SUMMARY:Agentics Day: MCP + Agents: MCP in 2026: Context is All You Need - David Soria Parra\, Anthropic
DESCRIPTION:MCP has grown from a specification into an ecosystem. In this talk\, David Soria Parra—creator and Lead Core Maintainer of the Model Context Protocol—shares where MCP stands today\, what the community has built\, and what’s on the horizon.\n\nWe’ll cover:The growth of MCP adoption: from early adopters to production deploymentKey protocol developments: authentication\, tasks\, and the extensions modelChallenges of MCP: Context bloat\, client support and OAuthWhat’s next: the roadmap for MCP in 2026 and beyondHow to get involved: contributing to the spec\, SDKs\, and governance
CATEGORIES:AGENTICS DAY: MCP + AGENTS
LOCATION:Hall 7 | Room A\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:c2e3c34d3b3b7a525b7090d8eb5bdb79
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/c2e3c34d3b3b7a525b7090d8eb5bdb79
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T123500Z
DTEND:20260323T130000Z
SUMMARY:Analysis in Action: Real-World Metrics Driven Argo Rollouts With AnalysisTemplates - Chris Detsicas & Antonio Jimenez Martinez\, Cisco ThousandEyes
DESCRIPTION:Rolling out changes in Kubernetes safely goes beyond canaries and blue-green deployments - it requires automated health checks. Argo Rollouts’ AnalysisTemplates let us bake automated checks and business logic into every rollout. Checks include success rate SLOs with Prometheus\, business-hour release gates\, API health checks and even dynamic E2E tests. These tests help us build confidence in our releases and catch issues early while only promoting what’s proven healthy. In this talk\, we’ll share how we have implemented AnalysisTemplates and walk through real examples using Prometheus metrics.\n\n
CATEGORIES:ARGOCON
LOCATION:Auditorium\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:32b93ce6ba0645f96c59968b6a25fc7c
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/32b93ce6ba0645f96c59968b6a25fc7c
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T123500Z
DTEND:20260323T130000Z
SUMMARY:GitOps Your Costs: Automated FinOps Through Argo Workflows - Kunal Das\, Cast AI & Hrittik Roy\, vCluster
DESCRIPTION:GitOps revolutionized deployment practices now it's time to apply those same principles to cost optimization. This session demonstrates how to build automated FinOps pipelines using Argo Workflows and Events.\n\nFrom our past experience cost optimization workflows that automatically rightsize deployments based on utilization metrics\, implement progressive cost reduction through Argo Rollouts\, and trigger cleanup workflows for idle resources. We'll show real implementations where teams reduced waste by 45% through GitOps-driven optimization. Discover patterns for cost-aware CI/CD that prevents expensive misconfigurations from reaching production\, automated weekend scale-downs for development environments\, and policy-as-code for resource limits. You'll leave with ready-to-use Argo workflow templates\, event configurations for cost triggers\, and integration patterns with popular FinOps tools. Perfect for teams wanting to operationalize cost optimization without manual intervention.
CATEGORIES:ARGOCON
LOCATION:G102-103\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:955fc205e69d118e77f1dce1422afb6d
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/955fc205e69d118e77f1dce1422afb6d
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T123500Z
DTEND:20260323T130000Z
SUMMARY:Network Flow Aggregation: Pay for the Logs You Care About! - Mereta Degutyte\, Anubhab Majumdar & Vamsi Kalapala\, Microsoft
DESCRIPTION:Hubble flow logs are a lifesaver for debugging and security. Until you look at the cloud storage bill.\nMillions of near-identical flows pile up\, turning observability into an expensive 'nice-to-have' when it should be a 'must-have'!\nWe’ve had ways to trim logs before by using FieldMask and Include/Exclude filters or using set times to make flows more relevant and less costly\, but those only go so far.\nOur new approach - Flow Aggregation. Instead of storing each flow\, we aggregate in-agent based on fields user actually cares about.\nThe result? Lower storage overhead\, quicker troubleshooting\, and leaner data that’s ideal for analytics and machine learning.\nAnd yes\, Calico users have had this for a while\, now Cilium does too.\nIn this talk\, we’ll walk through this new feature and why it matters\, show a live demo comparing raw and aggregated flows\, and share practical tips for tuning aggregation to your workloads.\n\nIf you love observability but hate runaway costs\, this session is for you.
CATEGORIES:CILIUMCON
LOCATION:Elicium 1\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:163a6bf44052381005e58bcd1e6902ea
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/163a6bf44052381005e58bcd1e6902ea
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T123500Z
DTEND:20260323T130000Z
SUMMARY:Policy & GitOps Unite! Kyverno and Flux Save Cluster City - Cortney Nickerson\, Nirmata & Leigh Capili\, ControlPlane
DESCRIPTION:In the metropolis of Cluster City\, chaos lurks in every deployment. Rogue CVEs creep through shadows\, and Entropy\, master of drift\, bends clusters away from Git-defined truth. But fear not! Two heroes stand tall: Kylie Kyverno\, guardian of Policy-as-Code\, and Flux Mason\, defender of GitOps order.\n\nWith their rhythmic sidekick Emcee Percy (MCP)\, this dynamic duo takes on the forces of misconfiguration and drift. Watch as unauthorized changes threaten the peace and learn how to:\n\nEstablish policy-driven guardrails to prevent configuration chaos\n\nCoordinate automated rollbacks & reconciliations for trusted production\n\nProvide real-time visibility and reporting through MCP dashboards & events\n\nTurn policy violations into actionable signals to close the GitOps loop\n\nAttendees will walk away understanding how Kyverno and Flux complement each other to maintain consistent\, compliant\, and resilient infrastructure. Join us! Be guardians of GitOps harmony with these powerful open source tools.
CATEGORIES:KYVERNOCON
LOCATION:E106-108\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:dc1e573aaea6fc93753ef56cab11154a
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/dc1e573aaea6fc93753ef56cab11154a
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T123500Z
DTEND:20260323T130000Z
SUMMARY:EU Cloud Sovereignty Framework Explained - Emiel Brok\, SUSE / DOSBA
DESCRIPTION:The EC Cloud Sovereignty Framework (v1.2.1\, Oct 2025) is the definitive blueprint for EU digital autonomy. Born from Gaia-X and CIGREF\, it moves beyond standard security to address critical dependencies on non-EU actors and proprietary lock-in. \n \n In this session\, Emiel decodes the framework’s dual assessment approach: the Sovereignty Effective Assurance Level (SEAL) and the quantitative Sovereignty Score. We will break down the 8 Sovereignty Objectives (SOVs)—covering Legal\, Data/AI\, Supply Chain\, and Technology—and map the journey through the 5 SEAL levels toward Full Digital Sovereignty (SEAL-4). \n \n Crucially\, we will demonstrate why true sovereignty is impossible without open source. Attendees will learn how OSS directly enables the highest SEAL ratings and how "EU First" policies empower organizations to reclaim strategic control. This talk provides a clear roadmap for anyone navigating the future of sovereign digital procurement in Europe.
CATEGORIES:OPEN SOVEREIGN CLOUD DAY
LOCATION:F002-005\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:572dcb27f753b7720f1742944517f6e6
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/572dcb27f753b7720f1742944517f6e6
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T123500Z
DTEND:20260323T130000Z
SUMMARY:Organising Your Code and State for Governance and Self-Service - John Keates\, Wehkamp Retail Group
DESCRIPTION:As your infrastructure and the code that defines it grows\, you'll eventually end up with a seemingly unwieldy amount of dependencies in a variety of files and modules.\nWhile you can manipulate the state to move and sort your way out of such a mess with splitting and moving state around\, moving to a more constructive separation of concerns allowed us stop the growth of our mess and come up with a much more productive design to migrate to.\n\nWhen we were working on this\, we didn't really know what we were going to end up with or what would suit us\, so instead of coming up with a solution right away\, we somewhat accidentally came up with a framework instead. While the way we're currently using is by no means the biggest scale this framework could support\, it gave us some much needed room for growth in the amount of providers\, environments and states we need to use to create robust\, repeatable infrastructure that allows for strong governance and self-service for everyone involved.
CATEGORIES:OPENTOFU DAY
LOCATION:Emerald Room\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:433cd2f1964865f2dd3dfb18e999dbe8
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/433cd2f1964865f2dd3dfb18e999dbe8
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T125500Z
DTEND:20260323T132000Z
SUMMARY:Build Your Golden Path Construction Playbook: A Maturity-First Implementation Approach - Atulpriya Sharma\, Improving
DESCRIPTION:Everyone talks about golden paths\, but most teams struggle with: how do you actually build them?\n\nYou've seen architecture diagrams\, attended talks\, but when you return to work\, you're staring at scattered scripts\, wondering where to start.\n\nThis talk introduces the Maturity-First Construction Framework - a progressive methodology that draws from the Platform Maturity Model.\n\nThrough a live demo\, we'll focus on three critical transitions: evolving scripts into validation frameworks\, implementing GitOps integration\, and enabling self-service using ArgoCD and Backstage.\n\nYou'll witness functional code being built\, illustrating how teams can begin with simple scripts and systematically enhance their developer experience. We'll explore battle-tested patterns for validation\, templating\, and GitOps integration.\n\nYou'll walk away with a proven construction playbook for building golden paths that scale with organizational maturity and deliver measurable developer productivity improvements.
CATEGORIES:PLATFORM ENGINEERING DAY
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room G\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:21504859cbac7656ff74746c15966944
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/21504859cbac7656ff74746c15966944
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T125500Z
DTEND:20260323T132000Z
SUMMARY:How We Built an Internal Developer Platform and Evolved It Into Open Source - Gang Luo & Kristina Kondrashevich\, Electrolux Group
DESCRIPTION:At Electrolux Group\, we operate in the IoT space\, powering connected appliances across global markets. As our engineering organization grew from 10 to 300 developers with only 5 Ops engineers\, we needed a scalable way to support delivery without slowing teams down.\n\nWe first adopted SRE practices\, but they proved difficult to scale across diverse product teams. Instead\, we baked SRE principles directly into our platform. Using Backstage\, OpenTofu\, and custom platform APIs\, we built an Internal Developer Platform (IDP) that automated infrastructure provisioning\, standardized tools\, and enabled self-service for developers.\n\nOver time\, the IDP evolved into an open-source platform focused on cloud infrastructure management\, making these capabilities accessible to others.\n\nIn this talk\, we’ll share our journey from SRE to Platform Engineering. We will cover the architecture\, lessons learned\, and how open-sourcing reshaped our approach to DevOps and developer productivity at scale.
CATEGORIES:PLATFORM ENGINEERING DAY
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room F\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:f61f4ce8ba482998aa58e3c105940018
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/f61f4ce8ba482998aa58e3c105940018
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T130500Z
DTEND:20260323T133000Z
SUMMARY:The New AI Coding Fabric - Patrick Debois\, Tessl
DESCRIPTION:AI-driven development is outgrowing the IDE and traditional build systems. A new layer of infrastructure is forming — the AI Coding Fabric — built to support autonomous coding agents..\n\nExposing an MCP service is only the beginning. To truly enable AI-native software development\, we’ll need systems for things like:\n- spec driven development versioning \, spec evals and spec registries\n- support for long running coding sandboxes for our Agents\n- proxies that easily switch between different coding models and agents\n- review at scale of parallelized agent artefacts\n- coding guardrails and tracing/observability\n- knowledge base systems optimized for development learnings to improve ourselves \, the team and the agents\n\nThis is already taking shape through emerging tools and prototypes in the open-source and cloud-native ecosystems. You’ll see how these patterns might soon extend — and challenge — the foundations we’ve built around IDEs\, CI/CD\, and service-oriented architectures.
CATEGORIES:AGENTICS DAY: MCP + AGENTS
LOCATION:Hall 7 | Room A\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:50a007bea5feadf1c84c5babfb39cbdd
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/50a007bea5feadf1c84c5babfb39cbdd
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T130500Z
DTEND:20260323T133000Z
SUMMARY:Observability for Your Internal Developer Platform: Instrumenting Backstage With OpenTelemetry - Ekansh Gupta\, Bindplane & Shivay Lamba\, Couchbase
DESCRIPTION:Backstage has become the de facto standard for building Internal Developer Platforms\, giving organizations a centralized developer experience for documentation\, services\, and tooling. But as these platforms grow\, understanding how they’re used and performing becomes just as important as what they provide.\n\nIn this session\, we’ll explore how to instrument Backstage with OTel to achieve deep visibility into its performance\, reliability\, and adoption. Attendees will learn how to collect\, export\, and visualize metrics that help platform teams measure usage patterns\, plugin health\, and system performance\, all using open-source tools.\n\nWe’ll walk through:\n\n1. Foundational Concepts: Why observability matters for developer platforms and how OTel fits in.\n2. Hands-On Implementation: Step-by-step instrumentation of Backstage’s backend using OTel SDKs.\n3. Integration and Visualization: Setting up an OTel Collector and integrating with metrics backends for live dashboards.
CATEGORIES:BACKSTAGECON
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room E\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:45423dcdef698282353a858ded1eb24c
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/45423dcdef698282353a858ded1eb24c
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T130500Z
DTEND:20260323T133000Z
SUMMARY:GPU Reservations: Maximizing Utilization and Fairness Across Teams - Sam Huang\, Cantina Labs & Thomas Chaton\, Lightning.AI
DESCRIPTION:Companies worried about GPU costs often turn to long-term reservations\, which can cut prices by up to 75% vs. on-demand. But executives hesitate to commit to long contracts amid shifting priorities\, while researchers dislike losing autoscaling capacity.\n\nIn this talk\, we’ll share how we merged the elasticity of cloud-based autoscaling with the savings of reserved capacity by building a custom platform on Kubernetes - one that orchestrates researchers’ training workloads\, abstracts away infrastructure complexity\, and keeps users informed. We’ll walk through the architecture and core capabilities\, from transparent\, adaptive preemption guided by team priorities to automated coordination with hardware providers for optimal resolution of hardware issues and dynamic budgeting that enables bursting into on-demand GPUs when needed.\n\nIf you’re exploring how to make cloud-native AI research infrastructure both cost-efficient and researcher-friendly\, this session is for you.
CATEGORIES:CLOUD NATIVE AI + KUBEFLOW DAY
LOCATION:Hall 7 | Room B\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
