BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T132500Z
DTEND:20260323T133500Z
SUMMARY:⚡Lightning Talk: Designing for Exit: Why Portability Is a Sovereignty Requirement - Alireza Rahmani\, Red Hat
DESCRIPTION:Portability is often treated as a secondary concern\, yet in sovereign cloud architectures it is a foundational requirement. Without a clear exit strategy\, organizations risk losing control over both operations and future architectural decisions. \n \n This lightning talk focuses on designing for exit as a first-class architectural principle. It presents cloud-native patterns that support workload portability using open standards and Kubernetes-based platforms. The discussion connects design choices around packaging\, deployment\, and dependencies to their long-term impact on flexibility and control. \n \n The session emphasizes portability as a practical expression of technology sovereignty and shows how early architectural decisions determine an organization’s ability to evolve\, migrate\, or change platforms over time.
CATEGORIES:OPEN SOVEREIGN CLOUD DAY
LOCATION:F002-005\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:371a2e002bbfdf754b0cff1936701e78
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/371a2e002bbfdf754b0cff1936701e78
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T133000Z
DTEND:20260323T140500Z
SUMMARY:Panel: Platform Engineering to the Rescue - A Practical Guide to Zero-Day Preparation - Hannah Foxwell & Justin Cormack\, Independent; Sal Kimmich\, GadflyAI; Erika Heidi\, Chainguard; Josh Bressers\, Anchore
DESCRIPTION:Do you remember your first zero-day? How about the most recent? Who was involved in the response? What tools did they use? How long did it take to patch that CVE? Are you confident you didn’t miss anything?\n\nMost security teams are outnumbered by developers by factors of hundreds or even thousands to one. Many organisations don’t have a single security specialist\, delegating that role to their infrastructure or platform teams.\n\nWhen asking these teams about how prepared they feel for the next supply chain attack or zero-day CVE the answer is always the same: “We’re f***ed”\n\nOur expert panel is here to help. Bringing deep expertise in security\, platform engineering and cloud native we’re going to get practical and tactical about how to plan for the next zero-day.\n\nBecause it’s not if\, it’s when. We need to be ready.
CATEGORIES:PLATFORM ENGINEERING DAY
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room F\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:ab5461e1b6afa59958baf5abfa86a3b1
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/ab5461e1b6afa59958baf5abfa86a3b1
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T133000Z
DTEND:20260323T140500Z
SUMMARY:Panel: Platform Resilience\, Built on Belonging - Diana Todea\, VictoriaMetrics; Stéphane Este-Gracias\, ITQ; Or Navon\, Friends of Dorothy; Milad Vafaeifard\, DHHWG
DESCRIPTION:Behind every high-impact Internal Developer Platform (IDP) lies a socio-technical system\, but many platform teams struggle not with YAML or APIs but with attracting and retaining the right talent. A vast pool of skilled engineers hesitate to apply because they don't feel they belong\, leaving organizations unknowingly missing out on innovation.\n\nThis panel brings together members of Merge Forward - a CNCF initiative uniting community groups across disability\, gender\, neuro- and speech diversity - to explore how designing for belonging drives measurable business outcomes: stronger Developer Experience (DevEx)\, higher platform adoption\, greater retention\, and ROI.\n\nThrough stories from platform engineers\, attendees will learn how empathy\, accessibility\, and allyship accelerate team performance and maturity - turning cultural health into a core metric of business success.\n\nBecause in platform engineering\, resilience isn't just built into systems - it's built between people.
CATEGORIES:PLATFORM ENGINEERING DAY
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room G\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:d226529c590ec5ad154fdb060c6aa796
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/d226529c590ec5ad154fdb060c6aa796
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T133500Z
DTEND:20260323T134500Z
SUMMARY:⚡Lightning Talk: How I Built My Laptop Into an MCP Server To Create Secure Cloud Native Infrastructure - Mahendran Selvakumar\, Tata Consultancy Services Limited
DESCRIPTION:Most teams still build new cloud native services by copying old YAML and hoping required labels\, probes\, limits\, and security rules are correct. This is slow\, hard to review\, and does not scale across many clusters.\n\nIn this session I show how I turned my laptop into an MCP server that can generate a first version of secure cloud native infrastructure from a simple request. I describe a service in plain language such as name\, image\, ports\, rollout needs\, access level\, and autoscaling range. The server returns structured output plus a baseline security posture. This includes probes\, required labels\, resource requests and limits\, safe container settings\, and allowed traffic.\n\nMCP acts as the control layer. The server does not change clusters directly. It produces consistent and reviewable output that can be approved and rolled out in a predictable way\, cutting review effort by about 40% and reducing drift across clusters by about 30%
CATEGORIES:AGENTICS DAY: MCP + AGENTS
LOCATION:Hall 7 | Room A\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:d140e971ead1cf60479b638be489c00b
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/d140e971ead1cf60479b638be489c00b
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T134000Z
DTEND:20260323T140500Z
SUMMARY:Forget Rebuilding\, Install Plugins at Runtime - David Festal & Jon Koops\, Red Hat
DESCRIPTION:As your Backstage instance scales\, the 'rebuild and redeploy' cycle for every plugin update becomes a critical bottleneck\, slowing down development and consuming resources. But what if you could install new plugins without rebuilding the whole application?\n\nWith the new backend and frontend systems comes an alternate and dynamic way of loading plugins with just a Backstage restart. We'll demonstrate\, with a live demo\, how you can distribute and install plugins as standalone\, self-contained assets provided to the main applications at deployment time.\n\nLearn how obtaining the final Backstage-based solution becomes as simple as adding desired\, already-built plugins to an already-built Backstage deployment. We'll show you how to transform your deployment from a monolithic build into a modular platform\, dramatically simplifying the integration cycle\, unlocking powerful cloud deployment options\, and enabling true distributed ownership.
CATEGORIES:BACKSTAGECON
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room E\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:5850fb8041c0e377fa369f893a06c6eb
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/5850fb8041c0e377fa369f893a06c6eb
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T134000Z
DTEND:20260323T135000Z
SUMMARY:⚡Lightning Talk: Accelerating Cilium: Our Journey on Offloading Cilium To DPU - Vijay Inavolu\, Marvell Technologies
DESCRIPTION:Can we offload Cilium 'completely' to a DPU ? How about doing this for a primary network ? Can it be done without adding any complexity at user level ? What if all nodes in the cluster don't have a DPU\, can it still work ? While we are at it\, can we also use the DPU as a node ? In a solution like this\, how much of host resources can be saved ? What if security polices are present which are HW accelerated\, how do these numbers look like ? Can we keep Cilium code changes minimal ? And can such a solution be opensource and DPU vendor neutral ?\n\nThese are some of the questions that we have started with for our work on offloading Cilium to DPU. In this session we would like to walk you through the challenges that we have encountered and the solutions we have created to achieve our goal. Demonstrated with Marvell Octeon 10 DPU we will show how this solution transparently offloads Cilium. We also have some intriguing metrics that can be helpful for end users of Cilium
CATEGORIES:CILIUMCON
LOCATION:Elicium 1\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:9bddef0b34a01ff5c1a4ee5689764421
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/9bddef0b34a01ff5c1a4ee5689764421
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T134000Z
DTEND:20260323T140500Z
SUMMARY:Real-Time GPU Job Scheduling Latency Prediction in Multi-Cluster Kubernetes - Sujoy Dutta\, Bloomberg
DESCRIPTION:Managing thousands of GPU-enabled jobs across a multi-cluster Kubernetes environment can create unpredictable scheduling delays\, impacting productivity and resource utilization. Bloomberg uses Karmada to manage ML and training workloads across data centers. This talk describes a production-ready Karmada controller that improves GPU scheduling with real-time queueing predictions\, transforming a laggy process into an efficient experience.\nOur system delivers precise queuing estimates through immediate processing of resource events and intelligent Karmada integration. Internal users can better understand job wait times with improved accuracy\, enabling better planning and reduced GPU idle times. Our solution combines real-time statistics with Kubernetes events\, seamlessly integrating with monitoring tools like Grafana and Prometheus. Attendees will learn how these innovations provide real-time insights with O(1) complexity\, enhancing prediction accuracy from daily averages to live metrics.
CATEGORIES:CLOUD NATIVE AI + KUBEFLOW DAY
LOCATION:Hall 7 | Room B\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:592e8b9ee7e6057659f6ceb43a2913dc
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/592e8b9ee7e6057659f6ceb43a2913dc
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T134000Z
DTEND:20260323T140500Z
SUMMARY:Running ML Challenges on Kubernetes (Part 2) - Hannes Hansen & Paulo Guilherme Pinheiro Pereira\, CERN
DESCRIPTION:Competitive challenges in machine learning serve as the central point for researchers to interact with their community. Nowadays\, popular services like Kaggle are used to share\, exchange\, and compete on such challenges. But they rely on participants having access to their own resources and are not suited for setups where data is kept internal or internal tooling is needed. Running your own infrastructure can help tackle these problems\, but it requires a platform to host the challenges and run the submissions. To run this platform\, a framework using Kubernetes\, Codabench and KubeFlow will be presented for running particle physics-based challenges at CERN.
CATEGORIES:CLOUD NATIVE AI + KUBEFLOW DAY
LOCATION:Hall 7 | Room C\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:d83a99b1f9b96ffbac636109ef98c0ee
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/d83a99b1f9b96ffbac636109ef98c0ee
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T134000Z
DTEND:20260323T140500Z
SUMMARY:Extracting the Last Microseconds of Performance From Containerized Workloads - Feruzjon Muyassarov\, Ericsson Software Technology & Alexander Kanevskiy\, Intel
DESCRIPTION:Cooking a perfect low-latency containerized environment is made of three ingredients: choosing the best combination of resources\, spicing them up\, and minimizing competition over them. While the first two ingredients ensure achieving the lowest possible latency\, the last two make it very predictable. This talk gives both a broad overview of what really matters\, and also ready-to-use recipes to try with your own containers.\n\nIn addition to a walk through of established technology like isolated CPUs\, memory and device locality\, and cache and memory bandwidth allocation\, this talk covers in more detail very recent enhancements in container runtimes and their effects. For instance\, combining two new features\, container-specific Linux scheduler and CPU power saving state controls\, one can reduce processes’ wake-up latency even by 99 % in some occasions.
CATEGORIES:CLOUD NATIVE TELCO DAY
LOCATION:G104-105\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:7abe684096f0c0aad89795e06b3bc3d2
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/7abe684096f0c0aad89795e06b3bc3d2
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T134000Z
DTEND:20260323T135000Z
SUMMARY:⚡Lightning Talk: Compliance as Code Meets Developer Portals: Kyverno + Backstage in Action - Gaurika Poplai\, Microsoft
DESCRIPTION:This session explores how integrating Kyverno with Backstage brings Kubernetes compliance directly into the developer workflow. Instead of treating compliance as an operations-driven task\, Kyverno’s policy results can be surfaced inside Backstage through the Policy Reporter plugin\, giving developers immediate visibility into how their workloads align with CIS benchmarks and organizational policies. Using Kyverno and Policy Reporter\, the session demonstrates how policy results from running clusters can be visualized per service\, showing pass/fail status\, violated rules\, and historical trends—all within the Backstage service catalog. Through a live demo\, attendees will see how developers can identify failed policies\, understand their compliance posture\, and take proactive action before deployment. By shifting compliance visibility left\, this approach transforms governance from a reactive process into a shared\, continuous responsibility embedded in the developer experience.
CATEGORIES:KYVERNOCON
LOCATION:E106-108\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:ddc2224e3414b92d408ebe0a0a4c3741
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/ddc2224e3414b92d408ebe0a0a4c3741
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T134000Z
DTEND:20260323T140500Z
SUMMARY:From Pods To PUE: A Digital Twin Approach To Sustainable Kubernetes Infrastructure - Matteo Bunino\, CERN
DESCRIPTION:As data centers face surging AI and scientific workloads and tighter sustainability targets\, even small gains in energy efficiency matter. This talk presents a Kubernetes-native approach to building a digital twin for data center energy optimization. Combining telemetry from Kepler/eBPF with the new Dynamic Resource Allocation (DRA) API\, we enable dynamic throttling and resizing of Intel and NVIDIA devices via RAPL and NVML/DCGM interfaces. AI models profile scientific workloads to infer resource intensity and criticality\, letting the scheduler adapt allocations in real time to cluster utilization and cooling conditions. The twin predicts the impact of scheduling decisions on Power Usage Effectiveness (PUE)\, stabilizing node utilization and preventing cooling or PSU spikes. This work envisions a feedback loop where Kubernetes and digital-twin models cooperate to orchestrate sustainable\, energy-aware data centers.
CATEGORIES:OBSERVABILITY DAY
LOCATION:Forum (Ground Floor)\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:d62040d6538be3878998fdd2110e98ac
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/d62040d6538be3878998fdd2110e98ac
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T134000Z
DTEND:20260323T140500Z
SUMMARY:Parity in Observability Across Different Platforms - Kirill Mikhailov & Liam Harrington\, Riot Games
DESCRIPTION:Riot Games is the leading video game company with millions of players around the world.\n\nStrong observability is essential to ensuring that we deliver the best possible experience to the players. Which amplified by the fact that most of our games are competitive online games where every latency spike may ruin the experience.\n\nBecause we operate our games at such scale - across multiple countries and regions\, we’ve discovered that we cannot just use a single observability platform due to technical and other limitations. And as a result\, we use multiple observability solutions across our ecosystem\, for some of them we do not have a direct access.\n\nThis introduce a new challenge: how do we maintain parity between different platforms?\n\nThis presentation is focused on how we navigate parity between observability platforms\, and how we utilise AI and classic approaches to that.
CATEGORIES:OBSERVABILITY DAY
LOCATION:E103-105 (1st Floor)\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:d2c6dffac7802cf917ee307ab8dc7c18
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/d2c6dffac7802cf917ee307ab8dc7c18
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T134000Z
DTEND:20260323T140500Z
SUMMARY:Tarmageddon: One Bug\, Four Forks\, and a Disclosure Scavenger Hunt - Marina Moore & Alex Zenla\, Edera
DESCRIPTION:You’ve heard of unmaintained software libraries\, but what about libraries maintained in four places? What happens when several people create popular forks of a project and then a vulnerability impacts all of them? When we found a parsing vulnerability in tokio-tar\, dubbed Tarmageddon\, we discovered what happens next. We’ll walk through this vulnerability and how the responsible disclosure ended up sent to four different projects. We’ll look at how this disclosure became a scavenger hunt for maintainer email addresses\, popular forks\, and dependent projects.\n\nWe’ll then zoom out to the ecosystem that made this disclosure so challenging. Why does rust have separate libraries for asynchronous code? Why do developers make a new library instead of adding features to the ones we already have? As a community\, what can we do to make this better? We’ll discuss the roles of open source maintainers\, foundations\, and community members in making our whole ecosystem more secure.
CATEGORIES:OPEN SOURCE SECURITYCON
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room D\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:e1c2348da32517a0255ef5c3710602d2
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/e1c2348da32517a0255ef5c3710602d2
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T134000Z
DTEND:20260323T140500Z
SUMMARY:Running Sovereign Cloud Stack Cluster for International Telecommunication Union: Lessons Learned - Martin Pilka\, dNation & Karsten Samaschke\, VanillaCore GmbH
DESCRIPTION:Many organizations today want to run their own private clusters which are fully open source\, to ensure information security and avoid vendor lock-in. However\, installing and operating such cluster is a nontrivial task.Sovereign Cloud Stack (SCS\, https://sovereigncloudstack.org) is the European open source project that develops standards for sovereign cloud infrastructures.In this talk we describe how we installed SCS based cluster for International Telecommunication Union\, what technical challenges we faced during the installation and how we successfully solved them\, delivering cluster in record 2 weeks time.First part of talk focuses on SCS architecture and its IaaS (Infrastructure as a Service) and KaaS (Kubernetes as a Service) layers. We describe components of cluster solution (e.g. control plane\, worker plane\, networking\, storage\, monitoring) and their interactions.In second part of talk we describe day 2 operations\, technical challenges we faced and how we solved them.
CATEGORIES:OPEN SOVEREIGN CLOUD DAY
LOCATION:F002-005\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:bd7bc0263eda6b31c822d282c269dcbd
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/bd7bc0263eda6b31c822d282c269dcbd
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T134000Z
DTEND:20260323T135000Z
SUMMARY:⚡Lightning Talk: Staying in Sync: Managing Upgrades in OpenTofu and Terraform Modules - Fabrizio Sgura\, Veritas Automata
DESCRIPTION:As known\, OpenTofu is an open-source fork of Terraform that maintains backward compatibility\, and in this lightning talk I want to focus on covering best practices for upgrading OpenTofu itself and keeping Terraform modules up-to-date. I discuss version pinning\, semantic versioning of modules\, and automated upgrade tools.\nFor example\, I talk about running openTofu init and openTofu apply across version changes\, showing how state files migrate. I also recommend tools like terraform-provider-migrate or CI bots to handle common pitfalls. The goal is a fast overview of how to safely evolve infrastructure-as-code configurations so they stay in sync with CNCF’s OpenTofu releases.
CATEGORIES:OPENTOFU DAY
LOCATION:Emerald Room\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:733f15080b1495b4dabb23f180fe1836
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/733f15080b1495b4dabb23f180fe1836
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T134500Z
DTEND:20260323T141000Z
SUMMARY:Decoupling Canary Deployments From DBs With Argo Rollouts - Anastasiia Gubska\, Chase UK
DESCRIPTION:Argo Rollouts offers well-known strategies for stateless applications\, but what about deploying stateful applications that use databases? How can teams ensure safe\, consistent\, and reversible database updates when rolling out new application versions? This talk answers by showing how to decouple database migrations from application deployments through backward compatible schema changes to the database that allow both old and new application versions to operate simultaneously during the rollouts. We’ll also explore practical strategies for common database refactoring scenarios\, including adding new columns\, renaming columns and tables\, and introducing new data types gracefully.
CATEGORIES:ARGOCON
LOCATION:Auditorium\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:3f091cfd17e4bad269ce9860583d4ba8
