BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T142000Z
DTEND:20260323T144500Z
SUMMARY:Beyond GitOps: Building Intelligent Drift Detection and Auto-Remediation in Argo CD - Ram Mohan Rao Chukka\, JFrog & Shibi Ramachandran\, ING
DESCRIPTION:In most of the Kubernetes clusters\, configuration drift is unavoidable and is often hard to detect until something goes wrong. ArgoCD does a great job with basic drift detection\, self-healing and auto-sync\, but in real-world enterprise environments\, not all drift is equal. Scaling a deployment isn’t the same as deleting a secret\, and treating them the same can lead to trouble.\n\nIn this talk\, we’ll walk through how to extend ArgoCD to handle drift more intelligently. Using Custom Health Checks\, ApplicationSets\, Resource Hooks\, and a custom controller\, we built a system that understands the severity of changes and responds accordingly by auto-remediating safe changes\, triggering approvals for sensitive updates\, and rolling back when things go wrong.\n\nThis talk is ideal for platform engineers\, SREs\, and DevOps teams looking to evolve their GitOps strategy with smarter automation\, policy enforcement\, and enterprise-grade reliability.
CATEGORIES:ARGOCON
LOCATION:G102-103\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:42fdb450132fc3726bec631edca551dd
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/42fdb450132fc3726bec631edca551dd
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T142000Z
DTEND:20260323T144500Z
SUMMARY:Cross-Cluster Progressive Delivery: Rolling Out Apps With Argo Rollouts\, Workflows and Events - Carlos Santana & Elamaran Shanmugam\, Amazon Web Services
DESCRIPTION:You've mastered canary deployments within a cluster. But rolling out apps across 50 clusters spanning regions and clouds? Most organizations deploy everywhere and pray\, or spend weeks on manual rollouts.\nWe treat multi-cluster rollouts like canary deployments at the cluster level. Start with dev clusters\, validate success\, progress to staging\, then production region by region—with automated validation and rollback.\nWe combine Argo Workflows and Argo Events to orchestrate cluster progression and Argo Rollouts for deployments. Workflows define which cluster groups\, in what order\, with what validation. Rollouts execute progressive delivery within each cluster while Workflows control cross-cluster blast radius. You'll see: live demo rolling an app across tiers\; automated validation before progression\; handling failures\; integrating ArgoCD ApplicationSets.
CATEGORIES:ARGOCON
LOCATION:Auditorium\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:a69417d7b0d6e4ea9c979806b482b8b1
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/a69417d7b0d6e4ea9c979806b482b8b1
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T142000Z
DTEND:20260323T144500Z
SUMMARY:From the Ranch(er) to the Dev: A Case Study About Simplifying K8s Cluster Setup With Backstage - Alex Speranza\, ImolaInformatica SPA
DESCRIPTION:The two main features of a developer portal are the catalog of the resources and the capability of executing actions on those resources. Most of these actions can be reduced to two categories: managing the state of resources or running one-shot tasks with them as parameters. While in the former case a GitOps approach can be adopted\, making the update of the resource state a matter of editing the content of a git repository\, the latter has more obstacles\, such as its audit or its possible non-idempotence.\n\nA challenging task is the onboarding of a cluster\, because its link with an SCM must be performed as a one-shot task\, but its configuration should follow a GitOps approach (for its idempotency).\n\nThis talk follows the exploration of a cluster onboarding process involving Rancher\, Backstage\, and Gitlab\, while also providing a real-world example of how to facilitate deployments on cluster where security practices\, like the use of Sealed Secret\, make the developers' job complicated.
CATEGORIES:BACKSTAGECON
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room E\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:1aeb61426a53c8e306cddb6e263d9d88
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/1aeb61426a53c8e306cddb6e263d9d88
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T142000Z
DTEND:20260323T144500Z
SUMMARY:Connecting the World: Your Hands-on Guide To Cilium ClusterMesh and MCS-API - Arthur Outhenin-Chalandre\, Ledger & Quentin Swiech\, S3NS
DESCRIPTION:Like Amsterdam’s canals connecting every neighborhood\, Cilium ClusterMesh links Kubernetes clusters into one cohesive\, global network. Navigating towards a single-cluster experience across multi-AZ or multi-region environments without sinking in operational overhead requires charting the right course through murky connections.\n\nIn this session\, S3NS\, the French trusted cloud from Thales and Google Cloud\, shares how they built a secure\, multi-cluster platform using Cilium ClusterMesh and Multi-Cluster Service API. You’ll learn how to:\n- Enforce network policies across clusters\n- Enable transparent service load balancing and DNS integration using MCS-API and service annotations\n- Seamlessly integrate with Cilium Ingress and the Gateway API\, and other controllers with EndpointSliceSync\n- Scale up to hundreds of clusters across the world\n\nAttendees will leave with a GitOps-ready blueprint for deploying and managing Cilium ClusterMesh\, your bridge between clusters\, clouds\, and continents.
CATEGORIES:CILIUMCON
LOCATION:Elicium 1\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:4dedc3eb91e83913e1aaf5197b900566
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/4dedc3eb91e83913e1aaf5197b900566
