BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T142000Z
DTEND:20260323T144500Z
SUMMARY:Kubernetes Meets Climate Data: Designing Analysis-Ready Data Cubes With Kubeflow and Zarr - Armagan Karatosun & Anna-Lena Erdmann\, EUMETSAT
DESCRIPTION:The exponential growth of Earth Observation (EO) data has transformed how the climate community processes and analyzes data. In previous years\, projects like the European Weather Cloud (EWC) and Data Proximate Compute (DPC) enabled researchers to bring compute closer to data across multi-cloud environments. The next challenge is making these massive datasets analysis-ready for analytics\, ML\, and AI.\n\nBut the biggest obstacle lies in the EO data itself—spread across archives\, stored in multiple formats (HDF5\, NetCDF\, GRIB)\, and organized into layers (L1–L3) with varying spatial and temporal resolutions. This fragmentation makes efficient access\, reprocessing\, and analysis extremely difficult.\n\nThis session presents how we built a cloud-native data pipeline using Kubeflow\, DuckDB\, and Xarray/Zarr to transform EO data into analysis-ready\, multi-resolution data cubes. Attendees will learn how Kubeflow orchestrates large-scale scientific data preparation and object-store-native access.
CATEGORIES:CLOUD NATIVE AI + KUBEFLOW DAY
LOCATION:Hall 7 | Room C\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:c947b16366be9e5b8448992ac75e1bff
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/c947b16366be9e5b8448992ac75e1bff
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T142000Z
DTEND:20260323T145500Z
SUMMARY:Panel: Agentic AI Infrastructure for Telecom - Yoshihiro Nakajima\, NTT DOCOMO; Ranny Haiby\, The Linux Foundation; Philippe Ensarguet\, Orange; Hui Deng\, Huawei; Yanjun Chen\, China Mobile
DESCRIPTION:2025 marks the dawn of agentic AI\, urging telecom operators to adopt it faster than cloud native tech a decade ago. To support AI agent deployments\, telecom infrastructure must integrate with cloud. Sandbox implementations like MicroVM\, Dragonball\, StratoVirt\, Firecracker\, and libkrun are already in use. Mitigating agentic app risks drives a new Telco Agentic AI infrastructure\, extending NFV to handle agentic workloads with secure sandbox runtimes.\nCloud native ecosystems benefit by incorporating agentic AI via secured virtualized containers\, speeding up telecom cloud and AI-native infrastructure rollout. Hybrid\, end-to-end orchestration offers a holistic view of future telecom networks.\nIn this panel\, telecom operators\, standards bodies\, and open source communities share views on AI agent infrastructure implementation and cloud native synergies.
CATEGORIES:CLOUD NATIVE TELCO DAY
LOCATION:G104-105\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:7cc0bc67b1d7c4f88ae50496e87cf8b0
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/7cc0bc67b1d7c4f88ae50496e87cf8b0
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T142000Z
DTEND:20260323T144500Z
SUMMARY:Beyond Admission: How Kyverno Extends Native Policies for Full Lifecycle Management - Erik Godding Boye\, Zenior AS & Mariam Fahmy\, Cloudflare
DESCRIPTION:Your Kubernetes admission policies are guarding the front door\, but what about the threats already inside? Native policies leave your existing workloads in a dangerous blind spot and offer no way to test changes without risking production. It's time to upgrade your defenses.\n\nThis session explores these critical gaps\, demonstrating how Kyverno provides a comprehensive\, lifecycle-aware solution. We'll show you how to “shift left” by validating policies against your cluster state before they're ever deployed\, ensuring safe rollouts. We'll then cover mutation from two angles: first\, using Kyverno's MutatingPolicy for admission-time changes on any Kubernetes version. Then\, we leap beyond admission control to demonstrate Kyverno's game-changing ability to find non-compliant resources already running in your cluster\, a power that native policies simply don’t have.
CATEGORIES:KYVERNOCON
LOCATION:E106-108\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:af80d90ca9cd7bc7b81e36e0c6733737
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/af80d90ca9cd7bc7b81e36e0c6733737
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T142000Z
DTEND:20260323T144500Z
SUMMARY:Designing for Observability - George Hantzaras\, MongoDB
DESCRIPTION:Observability is a key aspect of modern software design\, allowing teams to monitor and understand their systems in real-time. But designing for observability can be challenging\, with a wide range of tools and best practices to consider.\nIn this presentation\, we'll cover strategies for designing systems that are observable\, meaning that they can be monitored and understood in real-time. We'll explore the best practices and tools for designing systems that are observable\, with a focus on practical tips and techniques that teams can implement in their own projects. We'll also dive into topics such as instrumentation\, data collection\, and analysis\, as well as emerging trends in observability tools and approaches. Whether you're a software engineer\, architect\, or DevOps professional\, this presentation will provide valuable insights and practical takeaways on how a systems design and architecture can play a role in the system's observability and how to implement best practices.
CATEGORIES:OBSERVABILITY DAY
LOCATION:E103-105 (1st Floor)\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:aab40bf49b1231bf3bc883977d9b759c
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/aab40bf49b1231bf3bc883977d9b759c
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T142000Z
DTEND:20260323T144500Z
SUMMARY:One YAML To Rule Them All: Declarative Config - Jamie Danielson\, Honeycomb.io
DESCRIPTION:When I joined my current company\, I had to learn to write and maintain code in multiple languages. I didn’t need to be an expert\, but I needed to contribute meaningfully beyond JavaScript. Many engineers face this same challenge where they must occasionally act as a polyglot programmer. Then they’re told to implement OpenTelemetry\, dealing with each language’s setup\, idioms\, and quirks.\n\nWe needed a language agnostic solution. Environment variables helped a bit\, but they weren’t enough for more complex configurations. Setting an OTLP endpoint is one thing\; adjusting instrumentation preferences is another. Declarative configuration\, which uses YAML\, was created to bridge this gap. After several years of development\, it’s regaining momentum as the schema stabilizes and various languages add support. This talk will give a brief overview of declarative configuration\, demo how it can be used in a polyglot application\, and share the latest progress and what’s next for the project.
CATEGORIES:OBSERVABILITY DAY
LOCATION:Forum (Ground Floor)\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:fb991d0fa58fa4b1812c288394905fa3
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/fb991d0fa58fa4b1812c288394905fa3
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T142000Z
DTEND:20260323T144500Z
SUMMARY:Secure Your MCP Servers With OAuth\, JWT\, SPIFFE and More - Lin Sun\, Solo.io & Yi Yang\, IBM
DESCRIPTION:You have built your first MCP server and tested it with the MCP Inspector\, but it currently runs over stdio or streamable HTTP without HTTPS. Now you are asking yourself: should you rewrite your server to add authentication and authorization\, or is there a smarter approach? And what happens when you scale to multiple MCP servers? Do you really need to modify each one?\n\nIn this demo-driven session\, Lin first shows the hard way: modifying MCP server code to add OAuth support\, then rebuilding and redeploying. After that\, she introduces a simpler method that offloads authentication and authorization through an MCP gateway\, which allows you to secure your servers using OAuth\, JWT\, SPIFFE and other identity systems without changing or redeploying them. Finally\, she shows how her AI agent interacts with the MCP server tools securely\, with proper authentication and access control.
CATEGORIES:OPEN SOURCE SECURITYCON
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room D\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:3d859064fa81aa79f7491717bc14b3e6
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/3d859064fa81aa79f7491717bc14b3e6
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T142000Z
DTEND:20260323T144500Z
SUMMARY:Sovereignty and Open Source? How To Put Your Money Where Your Mouth Is! - Vasu Chandrasekhara\, Independent & Christian Hüning\, BWI GmbH
DESCRIPTION:Historically\, the military enforced standardization by leveraging its massive purchasing power to mandate its supply chain to produce equipment with interchangeable parts and specifications. \n Today\, software has permeated into every (civil or military) crucial system\, but interoperability remains an unsolved challenge in the high-stake goal for Software Defined Defense. With the relentless pace of innovation in software and current geopolitical urgency\, the luxury of waiting for negotiated interoperability between vendors is gone. We must shift to dynamic\, modular frameworks\, which can deliver immediate\, versatile\, field-ready integrations. \n We present the Germany Army’s strategy for an Open Defense Cloud that builds on multiple vendors\, all collaborating in LF\, CNCF\, and NeoNephos’ neutral OSS projects. We derive the ecosystem strategy leveraging the inherent motivation of vendors to use OSS. \n The OSS ecosystem thinking tied with purchasing power is pivotal for digital sovereignty.
CATEGORIES:OPEN SOVEREIGN CLOUD DAY
LOCATION:F002-005\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:c7663b1be263c42bfb313eb38a5826d8
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/c7663b1be263c42bfb313eb38a5826d8
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T142000Z
DTEND:20260323T144500Z
SUMMARY:Debugging Slow Infrastructure Runs With OpenTelemetry in OpenTofu - James Humphries\, Spacelift / OpenTofu
DESCRIPTION:Infrastructure-as-code deployments often suffer from performance issues\, with runs taking minutes or hours without visibility into bottlenecks. In GitOps environments\, this directly impacts deployment velocity\, but traditional logging provides insufficient insight into what's actually slow.\n\nThis talk demonstrates how OpenTofu's native OpenTelemetry integration brings cloud-native observability to infrastructure deployments. I'll talk through real-world scenarios where OTel traces exposed hidden bottlenecks—slow provider downloads\, inefficient state operations\, and API throttling\, all of which are situations that may be invisible in traditional logs.
CATEGORIES:OPENTOFU DAY
LOCATION:Emerald Room\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:c1717d88b1aa1188207adcc0d09acbc2
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/c1717d88b1aa1188207adcc0d09acbc2
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T142000Z
DTEND:20260323T144500Z
SUMMARY:Backend-First IDP: A Production Roadmap With Argo CD\, Crossplane\, and OPA - Abhinav Sharma\, KodeKloud & Aditya Soni\, Sailpoint
DESCRIPTION:The "portal-first" pattern cripples scale: teams build beautiful UIs (Backstage) over fragile\, bespoke automation\, leading to inevitable "portal fatigue." Our architectural lesson is definitive: backend-first wins.\n\nThis session provides a production-validated blueprint for building a resilient IDP with orchestration and policy as the authoritative core. We prove the theory with a focused demo based on a multi-tenant\, 100+ service environment.\n\nWe share the operational blueprint (and anti-patterns) to:\n1. Showcasing our minimal Platform API/CRD contract that wires ArgoCD\, Crossplane\, and OPA\n2. Detail how policy is authored\, bundled\, and promoted to prevent composition drift and policy sprawl.\n3. Demonstrate the end-to-end golden path\n\nThis approach cut infrastructure request lead time from days to minutes\, eliminated portal-only snowflake workflows\, and reduced GitOps drift incidents by 70%.
CATEGORIES:PLATFORM ENGINEERING DAY
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room G\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:b82bf558b6646995b48efa3b293c0665
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/b82bf558b6646995b48efa3b293c0665
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T142000Z
DTEND:20260323T144500Z
SUMMARY:Building Extensible Platforms - Hazel Weakly\, Nivenly Foundation
DESCRIPTION:Have you ever tried to build a house on quicksand? I can’t imagine it would work very well! The ground is so chaotic and the landscape itself isn’t reliable enough to be the foundation you need. It feels like you can’t even get started\, let alone build something sturdy enough to last. \n \nHonestly\, trying to build a platform in today’s environment feels just as chaotic. Things are churning faster and faster\, and just when you've finished implementing it\, something's deprecated and broken. It feels like things get thrown out just as fast as they're built. Quarterly planning? Long-term thinking? Some days they feel like relics of the past\, so how do we build platforms now? \n \nIn this session\, join Hazel as she walks through a journey of how she took a rapidly evolving environment\, where a platform seemed impossible to build\, and turned that chaos into something that long term success could be built on top of.
CATEGORIES:PLATFORM ENGINEERING DAY
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room F\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:0b224e5d858766ab4b727d8de01d317f
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/0b224e5d858766ab4b727d8de01d317f
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T145500Z
DTEND:20260323T152000Z
SUMMARY:Keeping Your Agents in Check: Layered Security for Agentic Platforms in Production - Evaline Ju\, IBM Research & Kelly Abuelsaad\, IBM
DESCRIPTION:As AI agents move into production\, safety\, reliability\, and security must extend beyond the models themselves to every layer of the platform. This talk explores a layered approach to securing agentic platforms\, from identity and authorization to guardrails and operational checks. We discuss how risks like prompt injection\, manipulated outputs\, and unauthorized tool access can be mitigated using both rule-based and AI-driven approaches. We will present a reference architecture where guardrails are applied at the Envoy gateway layer and cryptographically verifiable trust is established between agents and tools through OAuth 2.0 delegation with Keycloak.\n\nAttendees will learn the unique risks that accompany agentic applications along with practical strategies for scaling these safety mechanisms — all while maintaining performance and flexibility in production environments.
CATEGORIES:AGENTICS DAY: MCP + AGENTS
LOCATION:Hall 7 | Room A\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
