BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T145500Z
DTEND:20260323T152000Z
SUMMARY:Agnostic Workload Identity Across the Argo Ecosystem Using SPIFFE and SPIRE - Andrew Block\, Red Hat & Blake Pettersson\, Akuity
DESCRIPTION:In modern cloud-native environments\, securing workload-to-workload communication is critical. This session explores implementing platform-agnostic workload identity across the Argo ecosystem from Argo CD\, Argo Workflows\, Argo Rollouts\, and Argo Events using SPIFFE (Secure Production Identity Framework For Everyone) and SPIRE. Learn how the SPIFFE project aids in the elimination of static credentials and implements zero-trust security by providing each workload with a cryptographically verifiable identity. We’ll demonstrate practical patterns for integrating SPIRE across multiple Argo projects\, enabling secure service-to-service authentication\, automated certificate rotation\, and fine-grained authorization policies. Discover how this approach scales across multi-cluster and hybrid cloud environments while remaining vendor-neutral. Gain firsthand experience with real-world examples of securing GitOps workflows\, CI/CD pipelines\, and progressive delivery strategies that you can use today.
CATEGORIES:ARGOCON
LOCATION:Auditorium\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:615ccb6da5ab233cd0cd6542c1546217
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/615ccb6da5ab233cd0cd6542c1546217
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T145500Z
DTEND:20260323T152000Z
SUMMARY:From FTP To Argo CD & Argo Rollouts: An Adoption History Inside a Corp - Alfonso Ming\, LIDL HUG DIGITAL & Meritxell Rodríguez\, SCRM Lidl International Hub
DESCRIPTION:One year ago\, we deployed our SSO using Azure App Services and Azure Pipelines. Now we use semi-automatic releases driven by ArgoCD and Argo Rollouts. During this session\, we will explore how we have managed this migration process without downtime in a critical mission software with more than 90 million active users but also explaining why we have chosen these tools and what problems we've faced with. We will also show how our teams interacts with Argo tools\, having in mind that our teams are owners of their products but not of ArgoCD instance. This includes things such as the RBAC\, the management of secrets or clusters/repos and also how we have taken advantage of appsets and cluster generators as part of our Disaster Recovery plan. The last but not least\, we will explain how we can guarantee the reliability of the systems thanks to execute "last mile" smoke test in the beginning of a canary rollout (managed by Argo rollouts).
CATEGORIES:ARGOCON
LOCATION:G102-103\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:62e7fb19e2f7c9b1ed9c872a266dda7b
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/62e7fb19e2f7c9b1ed9c872a266dda7b
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T145500Z
DTEND:20260323T152000Z
SUMMARY:Think Backstage! Beyond Plugins - Debabrata Panigrahi\, Parseable Inc. & Jenil Jain\, Harness
DESCRIPTION:Teams ship plugins first\; catalogs lag. This talk shows a better path: extend and enrich the core data model so Backstage fits your domain.\n\nExtending the backstage model to reach where your software ecosystem is. Define new Kinds\, leverage existing kinds and types\, and extend as needed.\n\nUse processors to enrich the catalog\, ingest from SCM\, CI/CD\, cloud\, and HR for better health checks. Extend the UI to leverage the ingested data. Publish status checks for staleness\, missing owners\, broken TechDocs\, repo/template drift\, and contract mismatches.\n\nGranular permission for the extended catalog model. Add resource types and rules. Scope by namespace or team. Gate create/update/delete and relation changes.\n\nA catalog that's usable\, stays accurate\, governable\, and easy to extend
CATEGORIES:BACKSTAGECON
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room E\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:cfb6d1504e29390d399c848eb91b46e0
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/cfb6d1504e29390d399c848eb91b46e0
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T145500Z
DTEND:20260323T152000Z
SUMMARY:Cloud Native Promises\, On-Premises: Bump Your Load Balancing To V2 With Cilium - Mikael Johansson Länsberg\, Etraveli Group AB
DESCRIPTION:Etraveli Group manages millions of daily flight searches in our on-premises data centers. Our legacy load balancing relied on proprietary hardware appliances\, which often failed to deliver the agility\, scalability and dynamic environment demanded by modern applications. This made keeping our Cloud-Native Promises\, which rely on those very attributes\, very difficult.\n\nWe solved this by leveraging Cilium to bump our ingress and load balancing architecture one major version\, to a v2:\n\n* Unified Control Plane: Integrating LB-IPAM\, BGP\, and Gateway API to replace the proprietary stack.\n* Performance: Powered by eBPF to handle millions of requests with low latency and high throughput.\n* True Cloud-Native: Seamlessly integrates with Kubernetes\, enabling dynamic scaling\, multi-tenancy and resilience.\n\nJoin us to learn how we designed and deployed the next major version of load balancing\, and how you could do it on your own infrastructure with Cilium!
CATEGORIES:CILIUMCON
LOCATION:Elicium 1\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:1de12ae03467096e4c25bcb7265128e7
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/1de12ae03467096e4c25bcb7265128e7
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T145500Z
DTEND:20260323T152000Z
SUMMARY:A Guide To AI API Gateways and Semantic Routers - Max Körbächer\, Liquid Reply GmbH
DESCRIPTION:AI Engineering taking over fast the hype around GenAI and the cloud native landscape very fast adapts to this trend.\nThrough the complexity of providing product ready LLMs\, the options for managed services and multiple other providers who participate in this market\; the demand and interest for routing request and handle the traffic of AI enhanced solutions has spiked.\nLet us see what is out there on solutions\, for which use cases are those good and when they might make no sense.\nWe will compare them side by side to unfold the differences between solutions such like Envoy AI Gateway\, LightLLM or vLLM semantic routers\, to just name the prominent ones.\nWith this guide you are equipped to find your right communication handler.
CATEGORIES:CLOUD NATIVE AI + KUBEFLOW DAY
LOCATION:Hall 7 | Room C\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:9a4e2b5d1e2fe20c84bbdd553965286c
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/9a4e2b5d1e2fe20c84bbdd553965286c
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T145500Z
DTEND:20260323T152000Z
SUMMARY:When Models Write Malware: Defending Against On-demand Exploits - Shane Lawrence\, Shopify
DESCRIPTION:AI has made it easy for even amateur attackers to generate exploits on the fly\, and skilled hackers can iterate on initial access to produce targeted custom scripts in seconds. How do we detect purpose-built malware that can evolve faster than static signatures can track?\n\nIn this talk\, Shane Lawrence will perform a live demo of an attack and then show how to pair Falco runtime signals with an LLM-based script classifier to spot malicious intent in near real time.\n\nAttendees can expect to leave with an understanding of how AI has changed the field for attackers and defenders\, techniques for hardening containers against such attacks\, and a reference implementation for detection complete with prompts and helm charts for leveraging AI and open source tools.
CATEGORIES:CLOUD NATIVE AI + KUBEFLOW DAY
LOCATION:Hall 7 | Room B\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:3cd6bac150c888fdd331c120bc252070
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/3cd6bac150c888fdd331c120bc252070
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T145500Z
DTEND:20260323T152000Z
SUMMARY:Full Observability for Kyverno With Observability-as-Code - Imma Valls\, Grafana Laba
DESCRIPTION:The adoption of Kyverno solves the challenge of Policy-as-Code. However\, a new question emerges for platform engineers: what happens when a slow policy rule adds latency? A slow admission webhook can degrade performance across the k8s cluster.\nTracing the webhook's lifecycle is the fastest way to pinpoint any bottlenecking rule.\n\nThe next step in your GitOps journey is to make your monitoring as declarative as your policies. In the live demo\, you’ll learn how to monitor Kyverno's operational cycle using Prometheus\, Tempo\, and Grafana. We'll set SLOs and enable real-time alerts with observability as code\, including metrics and alerts for policy failure rates or slow webhooks\, and utilizing OpenTelemetry tracing to pinpoint what is causing a delay in the admission process.\n\nIf you manage policies as code\, don't let silent performance bottlenecks threaten your cluster stability. Join to learn concrete steps needed to close your GitOps loop and achieve operational control over Kyverno.
CATEGORIES:KYVERNOCON
LOCATION:E106-108\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:3d9bd77f04055bd504873cea34432510
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/3d9bd77f04055bd504873cea34432510
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T145500Z
DTEND:20260323T152000Z
SUMMARY:Let Me Be Your OpenTelemetry Champ - Pavol Loffay\, Red Hat & Nicolas Wörner\, OllyGarden
DESCRIPTION:Managing a production OpenTelemetry deployment is a major operational challenge. With so many independent components\, handling breaking changes\, tuning sampling\, and keeping pipelines healthy feels like a constant battle\, leading to a fragmented experience. What if you had an expert to manage it for you?\n\nThis talk introduces a powerful OpenTelemetry MCP Server that acts as your "OTel Champ." It enables an AI agent to intelligently manage your entire OpenTelemetry stack. This server profiles incoming telemetry\, understands breaking changes\, and automatically configures collectors and instrumentation based on real-time data. We will demonstrate how this AI-powered "Champ" automates complex tasks\, allowing you to achieve automated cost optimization\, dynamic PII filtering\, and hands-free collector configuration.
CATEGORIES:OBSERVABILITY DAY
LOCATION:E103-105 (1st Floor)\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:820e30228d3eb1fb1faaa1e2f5a7c80e
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/820e30228d3eb1fb1faaa1e2f5a7c80e
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T145500Z
DTEND:20260323T152000Z
SUMMARY:OpenTelemetry Gateways: Enforce\, Transform\, Route - Juraci Paixão Kröhling\, OllyGarden & Natalie Ujuk\, IG Group
DESCRIPTION:Teaching every development team about telemetry best practices doesn't scale. When bad data flows through pipelines (PII leakage\, misconfigured attributes\, cost-inflating noise) you need a centralized control point. OpenTelemetry collector gateways provide that enforcement layer between applications and backends.\n\nThis talk presents proven gateway architectures from production environments managing cloud and on-premises telemetry. We'll demonstrate validation rules enforcing semantic conventions\, transformation pipelines that enrich or redact data\, and routing configurations enabling backend flexibility without developer refactoring. You'll see real configurations: blocking PII\, enforcing mandatory attributes\, and filtering high-cardinality data before it leaves your premises.\n\nWe'll cover performance at scale\, security boundaries for multi-tenant environments\, and managing configuration drift. Attendees leave with blueprints and configurations ready for deployment.
CATEGORIES:OBSERVABILITY DAY
LOCATION:Forum (Ground Floor)\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:4c3441093981e1434f9cd2cb5f99f707
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/4c3441093981e1434f9cd2cb5f99f707
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T145500Z
DTEND:20260323T152000Z
SUMMARY:Simplifying Global Compliance for CNCF Projects With the OpenSSF OSPS Baseline - Madalin Neag\, OpenSSF
DESCRIPTION:Open source security is facing an increasingly complex global regulatory landscape. The Open Source Project Security (OSPS) Baseline\, released in February 2025 with partners including CNCF and FINOS\, lays out 40 practical requirements across three maturity levels\, covering areas like access control\, build and release\, governance\, documentation\, and vulnerability management.\n\nWhat makes it powerful is how it maps directly to major frameworks\, including the U.S. NIST SSDF and the EU’s NIS2\, DORA\, and CRA.\n\nThis session looks at how the Baseline (and its latest evolutions)\, together with the OpenSSF Global Cyber Policy Working Group\, helps navigate this diverse policy landscape. It shows how the Baseline is evolving to connect developer security practices with international regulations\, supporting compliance across multiple frameworks\, and offering a reliable\, evidence-based foundation to build trust across the global open source ecosystem.
CATEGORIES:OPEN SOURCE SECURITYCON
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room D\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:43ce00e1281b2ff8ee7992eed57ca83a
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/43ce00e1281b2ff8ee7992eed57ca83a
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T145500Z
DTEND:20260323T152000Z
SUMMARY:Bridging CNCF and OpenInfra: Kubernetes as the Unified Control Plane for Sovereign Clouds - Michael Schmidt\, SAP SE
DESCRIPTION:Europe’s cloud infrastructure landscape is fragmented making interoperable and sovereign cloud platforms hard to build. This session presents a technical deep dive into CobaltCore\, a Kubernetes enabled OpenStack distribution that bridges the CNCF and OpenInfra ecosystems. \n \n By combining Kubernetes’ declarative control model with mature Infrastructure as a Service capabilities\, CobaltCore supports workloads that cannot easily be replatformed to fully cloud-native designs. A containerized OpenStack managed by Kubernetes and the Kubernetes Resource Model enables a fully automated lifecycle from bare metal provisioning to workload delivery. \n \n The session examines using key projects of the Apeiro Reference Architecture\, the technical blueprint of the IPCEI-CIS initiative\, for bare metal automation\, vendor agnostic networking\, large scale Kubernetes operations\, security and compliance management\, and signed software delivery with end to end provenance.
CATEGORIES:OPEN SOVEREIGN CLOUD DAY
LOCATION:F002-005\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:79242780b4d898a1b4620cf7d006774c
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/79242780b4d898a1b4620cf7d006774c
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T145500Z
DTEND:20260323T152000Z
SUMMARY:Istio in Production: Expected Value\, Results\, and Effort at GitHub Scale - Mitch Connors\, Microsoft & Golnaz Rouhi\, Github
DESCRIPTION:GitHub has adopted Istio multi-cluster on tens of thousands of pods across 21 clusters to enforce mTLS and centralized authN/authZ for secure-by-default service communication. To scale mesh adoption\, we built automation to onboard workloads without app changes and introduced custom ingress gateways to route external traffic. Istio’s traffic management enabled incremental canary rollouts: new versions are first exposed to internal staff\, then gradually ramped to users with instant rollback on failure. In some cases\, least-connection load balancing reduced latency by ~15 ms.\n\n\n\nCome learn how to migrate to Istio at GitHub scale\, including the risks we mitigated (e.g.\, stale config\, sidecar saturation\, gateway load)\, and practical strategies for secure\, scalable service mesh adoption. We’ll also discuss what’s next\, including agentic traffic controls and Istio’s Ambient Mode.
CATEGORIES:PLATFORM ENGINEERING DAY
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room G\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:557935a444b154aff7c35c9e3ba07e39
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/557935a444b154aff7c35c9e3ba07e39
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T145500Z
DTEND:20260323T152000Z
SUMMARY:The GitOps Paradox: Why Your Devs Need an API You Don't Want To Build - Simon Koudijs\, ConfigButler
DESCRIPTION:Platform teams face a paradox: developers need simple APIs and UIs\, but building and maintaining them is a huge operational burden that pulls teams away from core platform work.\n\nThis session coins "Reverse GitOps\," an API-first pattern that solves this by placing a light Kubernetes control plane in front of your Git repository. We'll show how platform teams can define simple CRDs that act as a declarative API for their platform\, which can then be used to build GUIs (Backstage/Headlamp) or to allow devs and AI agents to interact with the platform programmatically.\n\nWhen a user interacts with this API\, the open-source `gitops-reverser` operator translates their high-level intent into a clean Git commit. This commit creates a pull request\, preserving your existing review process. Once merged\, this simple CR can be "exploded" into a full set of production-ready manifests by tools like KRO or Crossplane\, integrating with your existing GitOps workflow powered by tools Flux or ArgoCD.
CATEGORIES:PLATFORM ENGINEERING DAY
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room F\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:047501e1853f81a443d6409a99fd0290
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/047501e1853f81a443d6409a99fd0290
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T150000Z
DTEND:20260323T152500Z
SUMMARY:What Do You Mean It’s Broken? When AI Meets the Harsh Reality of Telco Observability - Piotr Matysiak & Iwona Wojdan\, Orange
DESCRIPTION:In Telco cloud environments\, finding the root cause across many Kubernetes clusters can be like searching in the dark—traditional observability tools provide data\, but not actionable insights.\n\nWe’ll introduce an AI-driven observability approach\, where an intelligent agent augments classic telemetry analysis with reasoning capabilities. The system combines live telemetry (logs\, metrics) with static knowledge sources (standards\, vendor documentation) to deliver context-aware answers.\n\nWe’ll walk through the proposed architecture and its dynamic query optimization decision layer—a mechanism that determines the most efficient strategy to resolve each user query. You’ll see how it integrates with multiple Kubernetes clusters and how it enhances a Telco AI Assistant\, an agentic system supporting lifecycle management (LCM) of 5G/6G networks via natural language. \n\nLet’s stop pretending data will just appear—AI and automation are only as good as the observability feeding them.
CATEGORIES:CLOUD NATIVE TELCO DAY
LOCATION:G104-105\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:2c5cfedeaf074e8e8b69e460ccb556dd
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/2c5cfedeaf074e8e8b69e460ccb556dd
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T153000Z
DTEND:20260323T155500Z
SUMMARY:Fantastic Vibes and Where To Find Them - Erica Hughberg\, Tetrate.io & Mauricio Salatino\, Diagrid
DESCRIPTION:Everyone's heard "I vibe-coded an entire architecture" or seen "AI built it beautifully but it doesn't work." This talk examines what actually works when teams use AI agents to code.\n\nWe look at four categories: which pull requests ship versus get reverted\, which agent bots developers love versus uninstall\, whether AI helps non-developers contribute\, and patterns separating productivity wins from frustration.\n\nIs isn't all about capability—it's also guidance. When teams use machine-readable conventions telling agents how projects work\, productivity jumps. When they don't\, agents fail silently. We'll review real cases of good and bad vibes\, including one team safely removing 100K+ lines while another wasted days on broken code.\n\nYou'll learn concrete patterns: narrow scope wins\, validation gates catch issues\, human review before merge\, and hybrid workflows for different task types. Practical\, evidence-based guidance on when AI amplifies productivity and when guardrails are essential.
CATEGORIES:AGENTICS DAY: MCP + AGENTS
LOCATION:Hall 7 | Room A\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:eb928d95ce2f6484c836df5b008a2a0b
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/eb928d95ce2f6484c836df5b008a2a0b
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T153000Z
DTEND:20260323T155500Z
SUMMARY:Declarative...ish? Fixing Hidden Argo CD Pitfalls in Your GitOps Setup - Regina Voloshin\, Octopus Deploy
DESCRIPTION:In the rush to adopt Argo CD and implement GitOps‑driven delivery\, many teams start strong but then quietly accumulate structural and architectural mistakes. These missteps may seem innocuous at first\, but over time they erode developer productivity\, reduce clarity\, introduce fragile deployments and undermine the very benefits of GitOps. This talk will zero in on four key anti‑patterns:\n\n1. Creating Argo CD Applications in a dynamic way\n2. Writing Applications instead of Application Sets\n3. Using Helm to package Applications instead of Application Sets\n4. Hardcoding Helm data inside Argo CD Applications\n\nTogether we will examine the hidden costs of those patterns\, how they manifest in teams at scale\, and concrete strategies to avoid them. Attendees will walk away with actionable patterns to ensure their Argo CD + GitOps architecture remains maintainable\, scalable and developer‑friendly.
CATEGORIES:ARGOCON
LOCATION:G102-103\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:28e465619cb82f93a69d12b92b9032b0
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/28e465619cb82f93a69d12b92b9032b0
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T153000Z
DTEND:20260323T155500Z
SUMMARY:Leveraging Argo Workflows To Move\, Migrate and Manage All of Your Workflows - John Keates\, Wehkamp Retail Group
DESCRIPTION:Like so many organisations\, we have a lot of history with Jenkins for building and deploying software as well as various other jobs and tasks to perform automations that need to exist "somewhere" and ended up in Jenkins as it was in use anyway. Fast-forward a decade or so\, and here we are\, with an organically grown stack of history with all the limitations and curious constructions that come with it.\n\nTo allow us to speed up and give our software developers a great experience with plenty of options to extend and customize we re-organised around Argo Workflows and ArgoCD to empower everyone to run the workflows and tasks they desire without having to re-invent the wheel every time a new new task comes along. By constructing composable pipelines with workflows we also got a lot of re-use out of common steps like linting\, security checks and notifications.\n\nIn this presentation\, we'll highlight how we arrived at these projects and what went in to designing this system.
CATEGORIES:ARGOCON
LOCATION:Auditorium\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:01aef9a5f6a9c18a5aea5f7e7ad0fb21
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/01aef9a5f6a9c18a5aea5f7e7ad0fb21
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T153000Z
DTEND:20260323T155500Z
SUMMARY:Unlocking the Catalog: Providing a Platform CLI for Backstage - Sebastian Poxhofer\, N26
DESCRIPTION:While the Backstage UI is excellent for discovery\, enabling powerful\, scriptable automation requires lowering the barrier to API consumption. Developers in CI pipelines or their local terminals shouldn't need to be `curl` experts to interact with the platform.\n\nThis session is a technical deep-dive into how we built an internal CLI to serve this exact purpose and how it developed into more. I will detail the implementation of how our tool connects to and abstract Backstage complexities.\n\nYou will learn how we integrated an external Identity Provider with a persistent device authentication to create minimal frictions for users.\nThis will unlock automation potentials of your like it has been for us.
CATEGORIES:BACKSTAGECON
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room E\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:f4d2cd049661453074af5b18a6de314a
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/f4d2cd049661453074af5b18a6de314a
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T153000Z
DTEND:20260323T155500Z
SUMMARY:One Policy To Rule Them All? Scaling Tetragon Without Flooding Your Cluster - Alessio Biancalana\, SUSE
DESCRIPTION:Like the canals of Amsterdam\, scaling Kubernetes security requires careful engineering\, balancing the flow of policies and enforcement without flooding the system with overhead. Each policy acts like a gate in a waterway\, controlling what passes through but too many and performance can quickly overflow. Enforcing security policies for every single workload introduces measurable performance and memory overhead. This talk follows SUSE's exploration of approaches to achieve strong enforcement while keeping overhead under control with Tetragon:\n\n- Designing and implementing a per-workload security model\n- Performance challenges observed\n- Techniques to reduce overhead\n\nAttendees will gain insights into eBPF policy design\, performance optimization\, and Kubernetes security scaling that flows as smoothly as Amsterdam’s waterways.
CATEGORIES:CILIUMCON
LOCATION:Elicium 1\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:d209973e6df9423ff4d834c499806aa1
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/d209973e6df9423ff4d834c499806aa1
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T153000Z
DTEND:20260323T155500Z
SUMMARY:A Deep Dive on How To Leverage the NVIDIA GB200 for Ultra-Fast Training and Inference on Kubernetes - Kevin Klues & Jan-Philip Gehrcke\, NVIDIA
DESCRIPTION:Multi-node AI training and inference jobs split workloads across nodes to scale performance and handle large datasets. With the introduction of specialized hardware such as NVIDIA’s GB200 NVL72\, these jobs are no longer limited by traditional networking fabrics such as InfiniBand or RoCE. Instead\, NVLink connects all 72 GPUs across 18 nodes in a full mesh network\, accelerating multi-node workloads with low-latency\, high-bandwidth communication.\n\nIn this talk\, we introduce a new abstraction called a “ComputeDomain\,” which users create via NVIDIA’s DRA driver for GPUs to run multi-node workloads on NVLink-connected GB200 systems. We discuss the intricacies of what’s needed to run these workloads securely\, as well as how the ComputeDomain abstraction leverages DRA to hide these details from the end-user. Additionally\, we discuss how this support has been pushed to all major cloud providers and integrated with their managed Kubernetes offerings. We conclude with a demo.
CATEGORIES:CLOUD NATIVE AI + KUBEFLOW DAY
LOCATION:Hall 7 | Room B\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:c2a33cf07db3ccb80805f4fa5eb274f0
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/c2a33cf07db3ccb80805f4fa5eb274f0
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T153000Z
DTEND:20260323T155500Z
SUMMARY:Scaling LLMs at Bloomberg Using Envoy AI Gateway: A Hybrid Cloud Approach - Xiaolin Lin & Aaron Choo\, Bloomberg
DESCRIPTION:The rapid rise of Generative AI (GenAI) and large language models (LLMs) is transforming industries - but financial services face unique challenges when deploying these technologies. Strict data governance\, stringent security requirements\, and the need to balance on-prem models and cloud-based LLMs demand an infrastructure that is both performant and resilient.\n\nIn this talk\, we’ll share how Bloomberg has taken Envoy AI Gateway - a CNCF-hosted open source project - from concept to production as a central piece of our GenAI platform’s tech stack. We’ll walk through how we utilized Envoy AI Gateway’s features\, highlighting the performance improvements\, scalability benefits\, and security enhancements we gained as a result. We’ll also discuss how we’re using advanced features such as secure authentication\, intelligent model routing\, and token-based rate limiting to safely and efficiently serve real-time GenAI traffic for financial applications.
CATEGORIES:CLOUD NATIVE AI + KUBEFLOW DAY
LOCATION:Hall 7 | Room C\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:72e4389594664f111af06ac7e6d6e0d4
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/72e4389594664f111af06ac7e6d6e0d4
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T153000Z
DTEND:20260323T154000Z
SUMMARY:⚡Lightning Talk: Operationalizing the NGMN Cloud Native Manifesto: CNTi and Sylva in Action - Martin Matyáš\, Tieto
DESCRIPTION:NGMN's Cloud Native Manifesto defines a north star for telecom\, but transforming principles into practice requires more than vision—it demands measurable criteria\, collaboration\, and testable outcomes.\n\nThe Cloud Native Telecom Initiative (CNTi) provides exactly this bridge. Through its open-source Test Suite\, the project codifies best practices for CNFs\, turning manifesto values like portability\, scalability\, and automation into verifiable checks. In partnership with Project Sylva\, CNTi ensures that application-level best practices align with cloud-stack requirements defined by Sylva. This collaboration offers operators and vendors an ecosystem-wide framework: from the cloud infrastructure to the CNF itself.\n\nLearning Objectives\n- How CNTi and Sylva collaborate to create a telecom cloud native framework\n- How NGMN's Cloud Native Manifesto inspires practical\, testable criteria\n- How operators and vendors can leverage Sylva and CNTi to accelerate their cloud native transformations.
CATEGORIES:CLOUD NATIVE TELCO DAY
LOCATION:G104-105\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:718dc39f75ba2135f4c98848d6c45ef4
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/718dc39f75ba2135f4c98848d6c45ef4
