BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T153000Z
DTEND:20260323T155500Z
SUMMARY:Kyverno Mutating Policies: Shifting Platform Logic Into the Control Plane - Rodrigo Fior Kuntzer\, Miro
DESCRIPTION:Ever wondered how to empower developers while maintaining tight operational control and security? This session delves into Kyverno's mutating policies\, the ultimate tool for modern platform engineering. Learn to shift complex automation logic down into the Kubernetes control plane\, ensuring every resource adheres to your standards before it even lands in the cluster. We will analyze production-grade use cases\, including:\n- Intelligent image registry mapping for global deployments\, ensuring secure\, fast\, and regionalized image pulls (eliminating egress costs).\n- Dynamic injection of configuration secrets\, sidecars\, and architecture affinities based on resource context.\n- Centralized configuration management for autoscaling endpoints\, decoupled from application manifests.\nDiscover the secrets to running these critical policies in highly available\, GitOps-managed clusters\, ensuring stability and preventing configuration drift.
CATEGORIES:KYVERNOCON
LOCATION:E106-108\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:b414c2f5a8592542bef291b0a03add3f
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/b414c2f5a8592542bef291b0a03add3f
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T153000Z
DTEND:20260323T155500Z
SUMMARY:Observability Without Borders: The OpenTelemetry Collector in a WebAssembly World - Evan Bradley\, Dynatrace & Pablo Baeyens\, Datadog
DESCRIPTION:From Kubernetes clusters to edge devices and serverless functions\, the OpenTelemetry Collector has proven to be a versatile tool for managing telemetry data. But what if we could take it a step further?\n\nIn this session\, we’ll explore how compiling the OpenTelemetry Collector to WebAssembly (Wasm) unlocks new possibilities for observability in constrained or unconventional environments\, such as browser runtimes\, language runtimes\, and other Wasm platforms. We’ll discuss the technical journey of adapting the Collector to run on Wasm\, highlighting the challenges of managing dependencies\, optimizing performance\, and tailoring its functionality to fit these environments. Whether you’re an observability enthusiast\, platform engineer\, or developer working on edge or serverless applications\, this talk will inspire you to rethink what’s possible with OpenTelemetry in the Wasm era.
CATEGORIES:OBSERVABILITY DAY
LOCATION:Forum (Ground Floor)\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:3346877e1b9fe979e2ed2f3cfe5ca7a5
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/3346877e1b9fe979e2ed2f3cfe5ca7a5
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T153000Z
DTEND:20260323T155500Z
SUMMARY:When the Codebase Starts Instrumenting Itself - Whitney Lee\, Datadog
DESCRIPTION:Commit Story is a GenAI powered\, automated engineering journal that is triggered by Git commits. But that's not the point. For the speaker\, this personal project became a playground for exploring how telemetry can inform AI coding assistants at development time.\n\nHer path to adding instrumentation likely mirrors that of many teams: an effort to follow OpenTelemetry semantic conventions\, reinforced first through documentation\, then later through a shared library of standards. Eventually\, she built an AI agent that reads OpenTelemetry docs\, discovers conventions\, extends the standards module\, instruments the code\, and validates that it all works by querying the backend.\n\nThis talk shares what that process revealed—how automation reshapes telemetry design—and includes a live demo showing how integrating OpenTelemetry Weaver formalized those standards\, enabling the Telemetry Agent to work across multiple codebases.
CATEGORIES:OBSERVABILITY DAY
LOCATION:E103-105 (1st Floor)\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:14a2a9c3d913973ccdb88b8bf9d9e0b0
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/14a2a9c3d913973ccdb88b8bf9d9e0b0
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T153000Z
DTEND:20260323T155500Z
SUMMARY:Thinking About Source Code Security in New Ways - Yongjae Chung & Justin Cappos\, New York University
DESCRIPTION:Code lives in repositories\, and we rely on forges like Github or Gitlab to host them. But in the growing age of software supply chain attacks\, it is becoming more necessary to have additional security in our own hands. \nWe would like to introduce gittuf\, a Git security system that brings security to the client side. With gittuf\, every developer can independently verify source code security policies\, giving them another layer of resilience against attacks. \nWith gittuf\, a repository can define its own policies and delegate authorization to maintainers\, who can also declare their own policies within their delegated namespaces. This provides a granular\, distributed trust model. gittuf can be used in tandem with existing forge workflows\, providing a smooth transition to a hardened repository for your projects. \ngittuf is an incubating project at the Open Source Security Foundation\, and currently in collaboration with multiple projects that are working to meet SLSA source track requirements.
CATEGORIES:OPEN SOURCE SECURITYCON
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room D\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:58a14af2294bcee63703c8f73836cbb2
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/58a14af2294bcee63703c8f73836cbb2
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T153000Z
DTEND:20260323T155500Z
SUMMARY:Beyond the DBaaS Trap: Achieving Data Sovereignty With Kubernetes and CloudnativePG - Floor Drees & Gabriele Bartolini\, EDB
DESCRIPTION:Digital sovereignty requires "operational sovereignty"\, that is\, the ability to run critical workloads on any infrastructure without proprietary cloud API limits.As global regulations like the EU Data Act set new standards for data portability\, organisations must prioritise architectures that ensure long-term independence.Managed databases (DBaaS) are the primary point of lock-in\, creating a "gravity" that prevents migration to sovereign clouds.\nGabriele and Floor demonstrate how to break this cycle using Kubernetes and CloudNativePG to build a cloud-neutral PostgreSQL architecture that satisfies modern sovereignty requirements.Attendees will explore how to meet business continuity requirements that remain identical across hyperscalers and bare metal\, while learning practical strategies for data-level portability. This approach ensures an organisation can move its most critical asset to stay ahead of regulatory changes without sacrificing the developer experience.
CATEGORIES:OPEN SOVEREIGN CLOUD DAY
LOCATION:F002-005\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:b01fc2e8a65c442776e3cb5e77ceea44
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/b01fc2e8a65c442776e3cb5e77ceea44
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T153000Z
DTEND:20260323T155500Z
SUMMARY:Testing Infrastructure as Code Using OpenTofu and Localstack - Pieter Vincken\, Cegeka
DESCRIPTION:This session explores how standard development and testing best practices can be applied to infrastructure engineering. We’ll demonstrate how to write effective tests for IaC using OpenTofu\, and how Localstack can dramatically shorten feedback loops by simulating AWS services locally. Attendees will learn practical techniques to validate infrastructure changes before they reach production\, reducing risk and improving confidence in deployments.\n\nKey takeaways:\n- Why testing IaC is critical for reliability and agility.\n- How to apply proven software testing principles to infrastructure code.\n- Hands-on examples of testing OpenTofu configurations.\n- Leveraging Localstack for fast\, local feedback without the need for an AWS environment\n\nIf you manage infrastructure or develop IaC\, this talk will equip you with actionable strategies to make testing a first-class citizen in your workflow.
CATEGORIES:OPENTOFU DAY
LOCATION:Emerald Room\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:64830336f7cc65e4d1b0ae73ba2f05cd
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/64830336f7cc65e4d1b0ae73ba2f05cd
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T153000Z
DTEND:20260323T155500Z
SUMMARY:Scaling Platform-as-a-Product Without Losing Your Mind - Eline Henriksen\, Telenor & Jakub Pawelczak\, Google Cloud
DESCRIPTION:As Telenor grew\, we reached an inflection point. Growing our platform user base to hundreds of developers\, platform development could no longer keep pace with our scale.\n\nTo accelerate developer productivity and manage this growing complexity\, we moved towards a Platform-as-a-Product (PaaP) approach—treating our internal platform as an intentional product with its own users\, roadmap\, and success metrics.\n\nIn this session\, Jakub from Google and Eline from Telenor will share real-world experiences building and scaling platform product teams to support hundreds of engineering teams.\n\nWe’ll explore what it actually takes to make PaaP work at scale\, including:\n- Building safety nets and paved paths that developers want to use\n- Driving ongoing education\, enablement and collaboration between platform and product teams\n- Continuously gathering insights and feedback to evolve the platform based on real user needs\n- Establishing effective communication in large\, distributed organizations
CATEGORIES:PLATFORM ENGINEERING DAY
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room F\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:2e6cf92145371c5a0264e4ddae9d6d14
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/2e6cf92145371c5a0264e4ddae9d6d14
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T153000Z
DTEND:20260323T155500Z
SUMMARY:When Platform Engineers Lead FinOps: Driving Reliability and $20M in Savings - Aditya Sharma & Mohit Kumar\, Expedia Group
DESCRIPTION:Platform engineers have long been guardians of reliability — designing resilient control planes\, enforcing SLAs\, and keeping 1\,000s of workloads alive. Yet cloud cost is often handed off to FinOps teams armed with scripts and spreadsheets\, unaware of how platforms actually work. The result? “Savings” that trade reliability for cost.\n\nThis talk is a call for Platform Engineers to adopt cost-conscious design\, operations\, and culture. As platform owners\, we know how systems respond to changes\, and where optimizations can be safely made without compromising SLAs.\n\nAt Expedia Group\, this mindset saved us $20M in 2025 while improving reliability across 500+ clusters and 10K+ workloads. We break down three key patterns:\n\n- Revisiting the Legacy\n- Establishing a View and Baselines\n- Embracing Re-architecture without Fear\n\nAttendees will leave with a field-tested playbook to embed FinOps into their platforms (no prior FinOps knowledge required)\, and a sense of responsibility towards efficiency.
CATEGORIES:PLATFORM ENGINEERING DAY
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room G\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:47d921914b7a1a30e21d79fd433d06a8
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/47d921914b7a1a30e21d79fd433d06a8
