SUMMARY:⚡Lightning Talk: What's Happening in Cilium? Current Projects You Need To See - Martynas Pumputis\, Isovalent at Cisco
DESCRIPTION:Cilium is one of the most active CNCF projects [1]. Recently\, it crossed 1000 unique contributors mark [2].\n\nIn this lightning talk\, we will present major developments currently happening in the Cilium ecosystem. Where possible\, we will include short video recordings from the project authors themselves\, giving them the opportunity to introduce their work directly to the audience.\n\nThe audience should expect a fast-paced visual update that highlights the development of the cutting edge cloud native networking.\n\n[1]: https://www.cncf.io/blog/2025/07/18/a-mid-year-2025-look-at-cncf-linux-foundation-and-the-top-30-open-source-projects/\n[2]: https://github.com/cilium/cilium/graphs/contributors
CATEGORIES:CILIUMCON
LOCATION:Elicium 1\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:1896382bd816ff1a2fd39eac56f91480
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/1896382bd816ff1a2fd39eac56f91480
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T160000Z
DTEND:20260323T161000Z
SUMMARY:⚡Lightning Talk: AI Meets Kubernetes: Langflow & GROQ in Automated Incident Management - Harini Anand\, IBM
DESCRIPTION:This talk is a personal journey that began with a simple desire: to make life easier as a developer assigned to managing recurring Kubernetes operational issues. Faced with frequent pod failures\, node assignment bottlenecks\, and the challenge of safeguarding formations from accidental deletions\, I initiated and built a proof-of-concept pipeline leveraging Langflow's visual orchestration and GROQ language for contextual LLM querying. This AI-driven system automates the detection\, diagnosis\, & remediation of common customer issues by combining Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG)\, cloud-native Astra DB vector search\, and multi-turn conversational interaction\, accelerating ticket resolution and improving cluster stability without overwhelming human operators. The talk shares this journey\, the system architecture\, and how this approach embodies a practical application of generative AI & RAG in Kubernetes operations\, fitting naturally in the evolving Cloud Native AI and Kubeflow ecosystem.
CATEGORIES:CLOUD NATIVE AI + KUBEFLOW DAY
LOCATION:Hall 7 | Room B\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:d0abb069e67a47e10dfe17b40e820eae
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/d0abb069e67a47e10dfe17b40e820eae
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T160000Z
DTEND:20260323T161000Z
SUMMARY:⚡Lightning Talk: Roche's Kubeflow Story: Large Models in Seconds\, Costs Cut\, Security up With Bottlerocket - Oswaldo Gomez\, Roche
DESCRIPTION:At Roche pRED\, our MLOps platform runs hundreds of ML endpoints for scientific discovery. Spikes in traffic were causing timeouts\, as our large (13.4GB+) GPU models took ~10 minutes for a cold-start pull. To ensure quick responses\, we were forced to set min=1 replicas\, resulting in over $100K in annual waste for idle nodes. This was unsustainable\, especially as we retrain and deploy new models daily. &nbsp\;\n\nThis is our end-user story of how we solved this by adopting Karpenter for rapid node autoscaling and Bottlerocket on EKS. We will detail the specific technique of using Bottlerocket's mutable data volume to prefetch large container images before pods are scheduled. &nbsp\;\n\nWe will show load-test data (20K API calls) that proves how we cut pull times from minutes to seconds\, achieving a 58% faster cold-start. Learn how this combination enabled true scale-to-zero (even for GPUs)\, slashed costs\, and enhanced security with an immutable OS
CATEGORIES:CLOUD NATIVE AI + KUBEFLOW DAY
LOCATION:Hall 7 | Room C\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:9540c2868455543e97d9742e8bd865b3
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/9540c2868455543e97d9742e8bd865b3
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T160000Z
DTEND:20260323T161000Z
SUMMARY:⚡Lightning Talk: Know Your Policy Level: A Lightning Introduction - Danielle Cook\, Akamai & Simon Forster\, Stackegy
DESCRIPTION:In just 10 minutes\, we will rapid fire through the Cloud Native Maturity Model’s Policy Maturity track. Think of it as a quick gut check for your organization. Do you have policy for cloud native? Are you translating rules from legacy systems and trying to retrofit them? Are you copy and pasting and hoping for the best? Or is everything humming along with full automation?\n\nThis session gives attendees a simple way to reflect on where they are as they move through KyvernoCon. You will get a fast framework to talk with your teams and leaders about what progress looks like\, why policy is central to cloud native success\, and how to keep leveling up.\n\nIt is also a call to action. The maturity model is growing\, but policy needs more real world input. We want your stories\, your strange corner cases\, and your expertise to help strengthen it for the entire community. If you are new to the model\, this is a friendly place to start. If you know it well\, come help shape what comes next.
CATEGORIES:KYVERNOCON
LOCATION:E106-108\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:bbe978a4198323ba5f94ff380b7857b7
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/bbe978a4198323ba5f94ff380b7857b7
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T160000Z
DTEND:20260323T161000Z
SUMMARY:⚡Lightning Talk: A Drop-in System To Accelerate Metrics Observability by 100x Using Sketch-based Approximation - Milind Srivastava\, Carnegie Mellon University
DESCRIPTION:Metrics observability workloads are growing in scale\, resulting in (a) higher cost to operate observability infrastructure\, and (b) slower query latencies.\n\nThe usual approaches to deal with these are:\n- sample data\n- roll up data\n- reduce data cardinality\n- send less queries\n\nAll of these approaches compromise the coverage of the observability infrastructure and can result in missing important anomalous behavior.\n\nThrough our research\, we have developed a radically new approach to achieve large scale\, low cost\, and low latency without compromising the coverage of the observability infrastructure.\n\nOur system reduce querying cost and latency by 100x by using 2 key techniques:\n- streaming precomputation\n- sketch-based approximation\n\nOur system is developed as a drop-in accelerator to an existing Prometheus-Grafana stack i.e. we require no changes to or replacement of Prometheus or Grafana.\n\nWe will release an open-source prototype around the end of 2025.
CATEGORIES:OBSERVABILITY DAY
LOCATION:Forum (Ground Floor)\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:47e8f68911bcdd2a1dd75706bf4bed9c
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/47e8f68911bcdd2a1dd75706bf4bed9c
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T160000Z
DTEND:20260323T161000Z
SUMMARY:⚡Lightning Talk: Semantics Matter! Lessons From Stabilizing OpenTelemetry’s System Conventions - Roger Coll\, Elastic
DESCRIPTION:After more than two years of collaboration\, the OpenTelemetry System Semantic Conventions group is nearing its first stabilization release. System metrics form the foundation of many observability agents\, and defining a consistent\, vendor-neutral\, and future-proof naming model proved both complex and essential. This lightning talk will share key lessons from the journey toward consensus — the debates\, trade-offs\, and breakthroughs that shaped the conventions. We’ll also explore how semantic conventions directly influence OpenTelemetry tooling (like the Collector) and bring tangible value to users — enabling meaningful alerts\, insightful dashboards\, and efficient data organization across observability platforms.
CATEGORIES:OBSERVABILITY DAY
LOCATION:E103-105 (1st Floor)\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:fa6483a1b1bd45a0511083ff8e96faa1
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/fa6483a1b1bd45a0511083ff8e96faa1
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T160000Z
DTEND:20260323T161000Z
SUMMARY:⚡Lightning Talk: Your Most Privileged User Isn't Human: The Agent Security Blindspot - Atulpriya Sharma\, Improving
DESCRIPTION:Your security team locked down Kubernetes. Then developers deployed AI agents needing kubectl\, cloud APIs\, observability access. You created service accounts with broad permissions.\n\nNow your most privileged identity makes decisions you can't audit\, executes actions you can't attribute\, invokes tools you can't scope.\n\nTraditional security assumes predictable workloads. Agents are autonomous - your controls don't apply.\n\nThree security gaps:\n- Lost Attribution: Audit logs show service account\, not which user or why. No accountability.\n\n- Permission Escalation: Agents need broad capability\, so they run elevated. Static RBAC can't express context-aware authorization.\n\n- Invisible Tool Chains: Agents invoke MCP servers dynamically. Security sees one identity\; attackers see an attack path.\n\nAs agents move to production\, these become active vulnerabilities.\n\nLearn what to add to security reviews before this becomes your incident.
CATEGORIES:OPEN SOURCE SECURITYCON
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room D\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:4533b4fe5a67a9b78e52522c9c28b744
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/4533b4fe5a67a9b78e52522c9c28b744
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T160000Z
DTEND:20260323T161000Z
SUMMARY:⚡Lightning Talk: 800 Reasons To Love OpenTofu (We Counted Them All) - Sagar Utekar\, CrowdStrike
DESCRIPTION:When an internal audit revealed 800+ Datadog dashboards with zero version control\, we had one month to move everything to OpenTofu without breaking security-critical monitoring.\n\nAs the SRE leading this effort\, here's what I learned:The Mission: Manage 800+ dashboards\, monitors\, and synthetic tests from ClickOps chaos to OpenTofu-managed infrastructure while maintaining zero downtime.The Approach: We built a custom framework tooling to automate 100% of the migration using Datadog API + OpenTofu import workflows with shadow-mode testing\, preventing production disasters.
CATEGORIES:OPENTOFU DAY
LOCATION:Emerald Room\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
