DTEND:20260323T161000Z
SUMMARY:⚡Lightning Talk: No Portal? No Problem! How We Scaled Our Platform With Just Terraform and ArgoCD - Maryam Tavakkoli\, RELEX Solutions
DESCRIPTION:Many platform talks focus on shiny developer portals and custom APIs\, yet many successful platforms scale without starting there. At RELEX Solutions\, we built an internal developer platform powering multiple teams across Azure Kubernetes Service clusters without a portal. Using Terraform and ArgoCD as our foundation\, we structured GitOps workflows that allowed teams to deploy infrastructure\, add-ons\, and applications independently while maintaining platform integrity. In this lightning talk\, I’ll share how simplicity\, clear repo structures\, and GitOps processes empowered our developers\, scaled our platform effectively\, and solved real-world multi-team challenges\, proving that sometimes\, less is more.
CATEGORIES:PLATFORM ENGINEERING DAY
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room G\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:000357a3b3dbf2db803dc758970c344d
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/000357a3b3dbf2db803dc758970c344d
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T160000Z
DTEND:20260323T161000Z
SUMMARY:⚡Lightning Talk: Production-Grade AI Isolation: K0s + Kata Containers for Zero-Trust Infrastructure - Prashant Ramhit\, Mirantis
DESCRIPTION:AI platforms in regulated sectors like insurance demand not only performance and scalability\, but governance\, auditability\, and trust built directly into the runtime.\n\nThis session explores how k0s\, a single-binary k8s distribution\, combined with Kata Containers\, provides a minimal yet powerful foundation for governed AI workloads.\nBy embedding isolation\, attestation\, and policy enforcement at the cluster core\, we demonstrate how governance is not an add-on\, it's intrinsic.\nEach model or inference workload runs inside a micro-VM\, ensuring data isolation and verifiable execution and aligning with emerging CNCF AI Conformance principles.\n\nAttendees will learn how to build reproducible\, secure AI environments\, from data center to edge. where governance starts at the infrastructure layer\, not the application tier.\n\nTakeaway: A practical blueprint for secure\, compliant\, and observable AI in insurance.
CATEGORIES:PLATFORM ENGINEERING DAY
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room F\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:db23b184f60093a02a93631ce4d3dbdb
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/db23b184f60093a02a93631ce4d3dbdb
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T160500Z
DTEND:20260323T163500Z
SUMMARY:Panel: Kill the Kill Switch - Reclaiming Digital Sovereignty for Citizens and Institutions - Rossella Sblendido\, SUSE; Vasu Chandrasekhara & Sebastiaan van 't Erve\, Independent; Kurt Garloff\, S7n Cloud Services GmbH; Jutta Horstmann\, Heinlein Group
DESCRIPTION:In an era of increasing geopolitical tension and systemic cyber threats\, the "kill switch"- the ability of a single provider or foreign entity to remotely disable critical digital services - has moved from a theoretical risk to a present danger. \n This panel brings together a unique group of stakeholders to dissect the real-world impact of digital dependency and possible solutions. We will hear the first-hand account of a former Town Mayor whose municipality suffered a major cyber attack\, exposing the fragility of non-sovereign systems. Experts from the Sovereign Cloud Stack (SCS) and the NeoNephos Foundation will join leaders from the Open Source industry to discuss the roadmap for a solution of the current crisis and explore: \n *How dependency on non-sovereign vendors amplifies cyber\, legal\, and operational risks \n *How open source and sovereign cloud initiatives reduce systemic risk and strengthen resilience \n *What municipalities and institutions can do to move away from closed systems
CATEGORIES:OPEN SOVEREIGN CLOUD DAY
LOCATION:F002-005\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:e0e826c65f1d4905a8a169bf1db3c5f0
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/e0e826c65f1d4905a8a169bf1db3c5f0
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T161500Z
DTEND:20260323T162500Z
SUMMARY:⚡Lightning Talk: “Tilt? Goreman? Make? Go Run? A Contributor’s Guide To Argo CD Local Dev” - Nitish Kumar\, Akuity
DESCRIPTION:A common question in the Argo CD Slack by new contributors is “How do I run and debug Argo CD locally?”. As a distributed system made up of several loosely-coupled components\, Argo CD can feel overwhelming to new contributors who just want to test a change or debug an issue. Should you use Make targets\, run components individually with go run\, use goreman or use Tilt?\n\nIn this talk\, we’ll break down the different ways to run and debug Argo CD locally depending on what part of the project you’re working on\, when to use tools like go run\, make\, goreman\, and Tilt with a live demo. You’ll learn how to run just the components you need to debug an issue\, and how to configure your favorite. IDE to debug components smoothly.\n\nWhether you're fixing a bug in argocd-server\, adding logic to the controller\, trying to understand why an Argo CD component isn't picking up changes\, or have ever asked “which component handles this?”\, this session will get you productive faster as an Argo CD contributor.
CATEGORIES:ARGOCON
LOCATION:G102-103\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:1ded1a24d2636d39a46abcd2d544b736
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/1ded1a24d2636d39a46abcd2d544b736
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T161500Z
DTEND:20260323T162500Z
SUMMARY:⚡Lightning Talk: The Backstage Builder Experience at Adyen - Sander Boumeester\, Adyen
DESCRIPTION:Come listen how Adyen has transformed its Backstage instance from a static portal with zero in-house built plugins into a thriving inner source platform with contributions from many teams across the organization.\n\nThis talk is ideal for teams managing a Backstage instance in their organization\, looking to empower their engineers to built in-house plugins.\n\nLet's dive into:\n- Tools for developers to build and ship plugins within minutes\, including Kubernetes and ArgoCD powered ephemeral environments and self-service guides\n- Guardrails for the quality of in-house built plugins\n- Roles within the Backstage maintainers team that help elevate the builder experience
CATEGORIES:BACKSTAGECON
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room E\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:1a32ab2d88e7ba18520e81605a7ba3f7
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/1a32ab2d88e7ba18520e81605a7ba3f7
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T161500Z
DTEND:20260323T162500Z
SUMMARY:⚡Lightning Talk: Closing the Gap: Fair North–South Bandwidth Management for Tenants - Weizhou Lan\, Daocloud
DESCRIPTION:In multi-tenant Kubernetes clusters\, enforcing unified north–south ingress bandwidth limits is essential to ensure fair resource sharing. Although this sounds straightforward\, Kubernetes currently lacks an effective solution.\nMost CNI plugins only support per-Pod ingress bandwidth control. As workloads scale out with multiple replicas\, it becomes impossible to enforce consistent limits at the tenant or application level. On the other hand\, community LoadBalancer implementations do not provide ingress bandwidth management for LoadBalancer Services. As a result\, operators often have to rely on external components outside the Kubernetes.\nIn this talk\, we will present a lightweight\, in-cluster approach built on Cilium CNI combined with Spiderpool. This design enables native bandwidth limiting for LoadBalancer Services\, making it possible to achieve tenant-level ingress bandwidth management within Kubernetes\, without adding external complexity.
CATEGORIES:CILIUMCON
LOCATION:Elicium 1\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:e703195365c4788d45fc6991f24977d2
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/e703195365c4788d45fc6991f24977d2
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T161500Z
DTEND:20260323T162500Z
SUMMARY:⚡Lightning Talk: Intelligent Traffic Routing for Distributed LLM Inference: Beyond Traditional Gateway Approaches - Zhonghu Xu\, Huawei Technologies Co.\, Ltd
DESCRIPTION:As LLM inference adopts Kubernetes\, intelligent routing has become critical. Existing gateways like Gateway Inference Extension\, LLM-d\, and Aibrix struggle with emerging patterns like prefill-decode (PD) disaggregation and distributed parallelism (DP+EP).\n\nThis session introduces **Kthena Router**\, a production-grade orchestration system for multi-model LLM workloads. Unlike approaches relying solely on engine metrics\, it uses **closed-loop control with adaptive modeling** based on connections\, token lengths\, load distribution\, and role-aware routing.\nIn this session\, we also will deep dive:\n\n1. How to do multi-model serving through routing policies\, eliminating per-model gateway deployments\n2. Native PD disaggregation support with prefill-decode awareness\, then removes dependencies on per-group routers or LLM-d sidecars\n3. Pluggable scheduling with fairness scheduling\, semantic-aware routing\, KV-cache aware placement\, and GPU utilization-aware balancing.
CATEGORIES:CLOUD NATIVE AI + KUBEFLOW DAY
LOCATION:Hall 7 | Room C\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:8e18f41651c3c6e7ffbf19244abe4183
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/8e18f41651c3c6e7ffbf19244abe4183
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T161500Z
DTEND:20260323T162500Z
SUMMARY:⚡Lightning Talk: K8s Issue #52757: Sharing GPUs Among Multiple Containers - Xiao Zhang\, dynamia.ai
DESCRIPTION:This issue has plagued Kubernetes for nearly 8 years: K8s issue #52757. The challenge of flexibly sharing GPUs across multiple containers is particularly prominent in AI scenarios\, where inference tasks are typically short-lived. As a result\, resource utilization becomes a critical concern.\n\nIn this talk\, we will share solutions and practices for implementing GPU sharing in Kubernetes\, focusing on two key projects gaining traction recently: Dynamic Resource Allocation (DRA) and the CNCF sandbox project HAMi. The presentation will cover the following topics:\n1. Challenges in GPU sharing.\n2. Approaches for sharing AI chips beyond NVIDIA GPUs.\n3. How sharing technologies integrate with projects like Volcano\, Koordinator\, and Kueue.
CATEGORIES:CLOUD NATIVE AI + KUBEFLOW DAY
LOCATION:Hall 7 | Room B\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:deb32e19e6eede5335e98bb07bc3e310
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/deb32e19e6eede5335e98bb07bc3e310
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T161500Z
DTEND:20260323T164000Z
SUMMARY:Beyond Match & Pattern: Mastering Kyverno with CEL- Koray Oksay
DESCRIPTION:Kyverno’s YAML-first policy model is easy to adopt for Kubernetes users\, but as complexity grows\, traditional match and pattern rules can become flaky or overly verbose. CEL (Common Expression Language)\, a game-changing addition that brings dynamic\, context-aware logic\, now supports Kyverno policies to overcome this. \n \nIn this session\, you’ll learn how CEL unlocks a new level of flexibility in Kyverno. We will explore how to write cleaner\, smarter policies by embedding CEL expressions into validation conditions\, preconditions\, and match logic. You’ll see real-world use cases where CEL simplifies policy writing\, improves performance\, and enables previously impossible or challenging tasks in pure YAML. \n \nWhether you’re writing policies for security\, governance\, or multi-tenant control\, CEL gives you the power to go beyond boilerplate YAML and build dynamic\, context-sensitive guardrails without leaving Kubernetes.
CATEGORIES:KYVERNOCON
LOCATION:E106-108\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:e117ae19bd9073b64a1f6444d3a298e3
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/e117ae19bd9073b64a1f6444d3a298e3
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T161500Z
DTEND:20260323T162500Z
SUMMARY:⚡Lightning Talk: Grasp the Real Worth of Your Microservices by Brewing a Truth Potion of Observablity - Yash Bhatnagar\, Google
DESCRIPTION:Every owner believes that their application is important\, and with constructs like Priority Classes & QoS\, it is easy to ensure an uninterrupted supply of resources.\n\nHowever the big caveat remains - how well do you know other applications?\n\nIn large clusters shared across several development teams\, setting such absolute values are often wrong & can cause unforeseen side effects - so much so that these constructs are effectively futile\, or maybe even worse.\n\nSo unless there is a perfect communication & understanding across development teams - a rare scenario\, eventually any cluster would reach a state where things need to be re-evaluated.\n\nIn this session\, Yash will showcase a real word case study about:\n\n1. How they realized their k8s priority constructs had become incorrect over time\, and how bad the situation was.\n2. How they went about fixing it - by gauging the real priority of applications by utilizing only a wide set of metrics\, interaction patterns\, and\, some clever thinking!!
CATEGORIES:OBSERVABILITY DAY
LOCATION:Forum (Ground Floor)\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:5a6aafcfbd091e7f81f7a08f168598d5
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/5a6aafcfbd091e7f81f7a08f168598d5
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T161500Z
DTEND:20260323T162500Z
SUMMARY:⚡Lightning Talk: “Metrics That Lie”: Understanding OpenTelemetry’s Cardinality Capping and Its Implications - Cijo Thomas\, Microsoft
DESCRIPTION:High-cardinality metrics just got safer with OpenTelemetry’s cardinality capping—SDKs won’t get OOM-killed anymore—but there’s a dangerous catch. When cardinality limits are hit\, new attribute sets are folded into a special overflow attribute. The problem? Metric backends like Prometheus don’t treat this overflow attribute as special—it’s just another label—so queries can silently return incorrect results.\nImagine querying error counts for /endpoint1. Once the cap is hit\, new errors for that endpoint get folded into overflow. A query like errors WHERE url="/endpoint1" might underreport errors—masking real issues.\nThis lightning talk explains how OTel’s cardinality capping works\, how it can create hidden observability traps\, how to detect when your queries may be incorrect\, and strategies to avoid falling into this subtle but impactful pitfall.\n\nThe spec for cardinality capping is already stable\, and support is rolling out across SDKs—now’s the time to understand its impact and prepare.
CATEGORIES:OBSERVABILITY DAY
LOCATION:E103-105 (1st Floor)\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:6c86fa450cb001a43057ebfa7b9db191
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/6c86fa450cb001a43057ebfa7b9db191
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T161500Z
DTEND:20260323T162500Z
SUMMARY:⚡Lightning Talk: A Supply Chain Security View of OpenSearch - Ram Iyengar\, Linux Foundation
DESCRIPTION:Supply Chain Software Security is a hot-button topic in the security and compliance domain of the open source software world. Specifically for end-user companies that are large\, risk-averse\, and depend on open source heavily. OSS projects\, and the communities that surround them\, are now compelled to adopt security best practices in order to position these projects as viable ones for commercial adoption.\n\nOpenSearch is a perfect example of a popular open source project\, backed by heavyweights\, and in use by a large number of companies. Therefore\, securing this project is of paramount importance for the community.\n\nIn this talk I intend to walk users through some security basics\, while showcasing how to adopt them for OpenSearch. Some of the information will include scanning the repository\, container images\, dependency management\, and deploying attestations\, among others.
CATEGORIES:OPEN SOURCE SECURITYCON
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room D\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:db67aff06197dede3ef848b95ef65a2b
URL:http://colocatedeventseu2026.sched.com/event/db67aff06197dede3ef848b95ef65a2b
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260321T190205Z
DTSTART:20260323T161500Z
DTEND:20260323T162500Z
SUMMARY:⚡Lightning Talk: Testing an OpenTofu Provider or Testing With an OpenTofu Provider - Toni Kangas\, UpCloud
DESCRIPTION:Testing is an essential part of software development. OpenTofu providers are no exception. However\, testing OpenTofu providers comes with its own set of challenges. The current testing tools promote usage of acceptance tests\, which could lead into slow tests runs and inefficient testing practices.\n\nThis talk presents examples about good and bad testing practices for OpenTofu providers as well as ideas on how to utilize the acceptance tests to validate functionality of the target system.
CATEGORIES:OPENTOFU DAY
LOCATION:Emerald Room\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
